WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.000
[Amit Varma]: We want tales of lust and carnage, greed and conquest, love and madness.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
[Amit Varma]: We want romance and betrayal and violence and murder.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And frankly history is full of all of this.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
[Amit Varma]: Our present times are relatively sane.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
[Amit Varma]: The stories that should fill our history books make all the most colourful story books seem so tame by comparison.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
[Amit Varma]: I read a book recently that had people getting trampled by mad elephants,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
[Amit Varma]: that had a father trying to burn his son in his bedroom,

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
[Amit Varma]: but instead getting killed by his son in his shower.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
[Amit Varma]: We had a sultan behead his assassin and carry his head around on a horse,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
[Amit Varma]: while kingdoms went to war because a ruler developed a crush on a girl

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and decided he had to abduct her and have her in his harem.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a mad story book and it makes the Game of Thrones look like a children's book.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a book you won't put down when you start reading it,

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
[Amit Varma]: especially if you're reading it on your smartphone,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
[Amit Varma]: because hey, who puts down their smartphones these days?

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen,

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
[Unknown]: our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural science.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bhadwa.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Today's subject is the history of the Deccan.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Now for most people the Deccan is all about Shivaji versus the Mughals,

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: but actually the Deccan has an incredibly colourful history

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
