00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:43.000
[Guest]: Manu, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
[Guest]: Thank you for having me. I've been hearing for a few months now, but it's good to be on the program finally.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:49.000
[Amit Varma]: Great to hear.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'm very curious about how you became a historian.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, first of all, you're like 28 years old, and you've already written two acclaimed books of history.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So how did you sort of get drawn towards writing history?

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:06.000
[Guest]: Well, it began with stories, because more than history as such, it was the stories in my own family.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
[Guest]: Because every now and then, you know, I grew up in Pune, but we would go to Kerala to my grandmother's place.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
[Guest]: And she would tell these vivid, reverting stories about her own family members.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
[Guest]: And she had this fascinating way of telling stories without any censorship.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.000
[Guest]: Because normally you have this image of your grandmother as somebody who tells you stories with, you know, moral lessons at the end of it.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.000
[Guest]: My grandmother told me no such story.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.000
[Guest]: She told me about her uncles and how many illegitimate children they had,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
[Guest]: how many wives they married, how they discarded their wives, how the system there worked, you know,

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
[Guest]: how when she was growing up, what the agrarian economy was.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
[Guest]: These were the things I grew up listening to.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
[Guest]: So it was a story of groves and gods and fighting goddesses and, you know,

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: a great-great-great grandmother who could tame an elephant and things like that.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.000
[Guest]: So I started getting interested in these people.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
[Guest]: And, you know, I refer to this uncle with illegitimate kids, for example.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
[Guest]: The idea was that she'd say it in such hilarious ways, these stories.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
[Guest]: I realized very quickly that although these people were not of my time,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
[Guest]: their context was different, their period was different completely,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
[Guest]: they were not like us human beings.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.000
[Guest]: They were made of flesh and blood.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
[Guest]: They had the same instincts and impulses.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:14.000
[Guest]: And that to me was fascinating, the idea that they may have lived 150 years before me,

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
[Guest]: but they were just like me in terms of what they were trying to do, you know, who they were as people.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Guest]: And once you start seeing history through the eyes of the people who make history,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
[Guest]: then you start realizing that it's easier to connect with history.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
[Guest]: So then for me, the journey then moved to biographies of people.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: I started reading about people in history.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
[Guest]: And then, of course, when I was about 18, I came across this long-forgotten Malayali queen,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
[Guest]: the Setulakshmi Bai of Travancore.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: And the story was so fascinating for me that, you know,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
[Guest]: it launched something that lasted six years.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Guest]: And from 19 to 25, I was working on my first book, which came out in 2015,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
[Guest]: The Ivory Throne.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
[Guest]: And, you know, then, of course, I came to the Deccan, which was launched earlier this year.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:58.000
[Amit Varma]: So I remember when I was 19, back in the day, pretty much the only thing I knew was how to mix Old Monk and Coke.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:05:59.000
[Amit Varma]: How do you know how to do history?

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.000
[Amit Varma]: How do you learn that?

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
[Guest]: What is doing history?

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
[Guest]: Doing history, I suppose there's no single answer to doing history.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.000
[Guest]: Of course, it's a science in a way, it needs a certain amount of responsibility.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
[Guest]: But I didn't go into it thinking, oh, I'm going to write this book this way or whatever.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest]: That evolved over time.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Guest]: At 19, you know, I suppose when I went in, I was looking for this fascinating story.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:19.000
[Guest]: I was collecting material.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
[Guest]: I did a skeletal draft.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
[Guest]: But I didn't know what the hell I was actually doing.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:28.000
[Guest]: But then, luckily for me, because I invested the time in it, which was six years, I grew as a person.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
[Guest]: It wasn't the 19-year-old who went into the book, who finished the book in 2015.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
[Guest]: You know, I had changed as a person.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
[Guest]: The book changed me just as much as I ended up writing the book.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.000
[Guest]: And in that process, I did a master's degree at the time, which I had to do a thesis.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.000
[Guest]: So at university, we were taught about research methods, you know, how to do your footnoting, how to find material, things like that.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:56.000
[Guest]: Although that was in international relations, the point was those skills, so to speak, ended up, you know, being perfectly applicable to history as well.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: And I started figuring out how to access archives, how to go about getting your material.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
[Guest]: And then, naturally, things started falling into place.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:10.000
[Guest]: So you have a combination of your material, your story, as well as, you know, everything that needs to finally come together and create that recipe for it to work.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
[Guest]: So, you know, I put together three or four or five drafts, actually.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
[Guest]: Some parts of the book are five drafts.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:22.000
[Guest]: And the interesting thing is the final draft, the final version of the book, was entirely trying to read it from the perspective of the reader.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
[Guest]: In the sense that for the first three or four drafts, I was writing what I wanted to say.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Guest]: It was the story I wanted to tell.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:33.000
[Guest]: But the final version, before it went to press, for six months, was trying to figure out how is the reader going to read this.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
[Guest]: That's where the difference is, right?

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.000
[Guest]: So you have academic historians who populate the seminar circuit.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
[Guest]: But I didn't want to do that because I found there are these fascinating stories.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Guest]: They need to be conveyed to a larger audience.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:51.000
[Guest]: You have to have a bridge that takes solidly researched history, but in an accessible fashion to as large an audience as possible.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
[Guest]: So then you need to know what the audience is thinking.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
[Guest]: You need to figure out what appeals to them.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
[Guest]: Your language has to have a certain elegance.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:05.000
[Guest]: So for me, doing history is academic rigor in terms of how you approach your material, how you interrogate your material, and how you draw your conclusions.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:12.000
[Guest]: But also writing in a fashion that is literary, that is attractive, that tries and reaches out to as many people as possible.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.000
[Guest]: Because this is, frankly, everybody's heritage.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:21.000
[Guest]: If the stories could fascinate me in my teens, someone needs to sort of disseminate them for a larger audience.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
[Guest]: And doing that means your style of writing also matters.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And you, of course, talking about your book, Ivory Throne, which I'd encourage all my listeners to check out.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And what was sort of the early books which gave you a sense that history is not a boring subject,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:40.000
[Amit Varma]: but it can, you know, be told in as fascinating and gripping and engrossing a manner as a novel or a storybook?

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.000
[Guest]: You know, funnily enough, it wasn't so much history books that influenced the writing itself,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
[Guest]: which was, for example, P. G. Woodhouse, I keep saying that, you know, there's a certain irreverence that I picked up from there,

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
[Guest]: which you may have found in Rebel Sultan, as well as my book on the Deccan,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
[Guest]: which is that every now and then, I mean, the whole idea is to say that although this is history, although this is serious business,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
[Guest]: never take yourself or your writing, or even frankly, any of these people too seriously.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
[Guest]: Because it wasn't like they woke up in the morning and decided, oh, we're making history today.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Guest]: No, they were just going about their lives.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:14.000
[Guest]: So we realized that we're able to look at history from a different perspective in a different way

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
[Guest]: without getting completely overawed by what is happening.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:23.000
[Guest]: But otherwise, in terms of writing history in an accessible way, William Dalrymple gets great credit.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Guest]: Because frankly, for me, in my early teens, his books were the ones that really, you know, stood out and told me that,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[Guest]: hold on, this is history, it's archival material, but it's sold so well.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
[Guest]: It's told so richly that you feel an inducement to turn the page, you want to turn the page.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
[Guest]: And that is what I wanted to do as well.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.000
[Guest]: Just as the stories I heard in my family, you know, could make me sit up with pleasure and delight.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
[Guest]: This was, I was reading a book that was making me do the same thing.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
[Guest]: And I thought, you know, those are the kind of books that I want to do.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: So partly it was fiction more than nonfiction.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: Your P.G. Woodhouse of the world, Aubrey Menon and his Ramayana retold.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
[Guest]: It's a satirical take on the Ramayana. It was one of the earliest books to be banned in India.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.000
[Guest]: But it's fascinating to look at how one man could take this grand epic and give it this very interesting twist.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:12.000
[Guest]: And, of course, then finally Dalrymple and, you know, all the other writers who were writing at that time.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
[Amit Varma]: And before we start talking about the rebel sultans, which, by the way, I found, you know,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
[Amit Varma]: something you wouldn't expect from a book of history is full of LOL moments, not just in the events you describe,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
[Amit Varma]: but also the way you write them, as you said.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:27.000
[Amit Varma]: But before we get to that, you also mentioned that the process of writing The Ivory Throne changed you as a person.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
[Amit Varma]: In what ways did it change you or the way you look at the world?

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest]: Well, if you looked at The Ivory Throne, it's a 700-page book.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:40.000
[Guest]: So, I mean, I didn't realize it was going to be such a long book, but obviously, you know, it proved to be a fairly long book.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:47.000
[Guest]: But, you know, going in at 19 meant that I wasn't an introverted person who was used to sitting at a desk and plodding away for hours every day.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:53.000
[Guest]: So, but once the story sort of, you know, hooked me, it took a life of its own and then everything became about that.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:58.000
[Guest]: So I had in 2009 access to all my protagonist's personal letters and so on.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
[Guest]: But then I realized the other piece in the puzzle was in the British archives in London.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
[Guest]: So I wanted to go there.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
[Guest]: How do you convince your parents at 19 or 20 that you want to go abroad and write a book?

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
[Guest]: So obviously I said, oh, I want to do a master's degree. Will you fund it?

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest]: Of course, you know, parents being good parents, they said, of course, we'll fund it.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:14.000
[Guest]: You know, there you go.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
[Guest]: So then I chose a university where the workload would be lower.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Guest]: So all the rest of my time I had access to the library.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:25.000
[Guest]: So my routine was normally classes in the morning and then rush off to the archive and sit there till whenever they shut,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:29.000
[Guest]: which was normally five o'clock the archive shuts and then the rest of the library at eight o'clock,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:36.000
[Guest]: which meant that from the age of 20, I was stuck, you know, from classes and then sitting in a room full of quiet people for about six, seven hours a day

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
[Guest]: and then coming home and then doing my business.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Guest]: So, so much so my friends started calling me the monk because I wouldn't go out.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:43.000
[Guest]: I wouldn't go out drinking.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:48.000
[Guest]: If I drank on a Friday, then, you know, you'd end up sleeping in late on Saturdays, where Saturday is the library shut early.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
[Guest]: So I couldn't waste time there.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
[Guest]: So it took a toll in terms of my personal life, what is happening in my social life.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
[Guest]: But all the same, you know, I have no regrets as such.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
[Guest]: Work, of course, you know, I graduated, came to Delhi, started working in Parliament with Shashi Tharoor.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
[Guest]: That took its own toll.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:08.000
[Guest]: So then from nine to nine, I was working on his job, you know, running his parliamentary office in Delhi.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
[Guest]: And then about 10 o'clock to three was my writing time.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
[Guest]: So I got into this routine of sleeping four hours a night.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
[Guest]: And strangely enough, after all these years, I haven't been able to shake it off.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Guest]: I still can't sleep well.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
[Guest]: Even if I go to bed at 11, I stay there with my eyes open.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest]: So in many ways, you know, the process of writing a book and being attached to that project for six years,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:32.000
[Guest]: meant that everything came to, everything depended on what the project needed at any given time.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: So where I was, so when I needed the National Archives in Delhi, I came and worked in Delhi.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
[Guest]: When I wanted the British Archives, again, I went back to London and started working there.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest]: Finally, it was in 2014, I realized it's been five years since I've been doing this.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: I can't allow this to go on indefinitely, because it's taking over my life.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
[Guest]: So one way or the other, before I'm 25, the book has to be done.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Guest]: So that's when I finally shut the project and, you know, got on with the task of publishing it.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And from there, how did you move on to the Deccan as a subject?

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Guest]: The Deccan came, so the ivory throne relates to my Malayali heritage.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
[Guest]: As somebody, as a Malayali who grew up outside Kerala,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
[Guest]: I was always interested in the story of my ancestors and the past in Kerala.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.000
[Guest]: But I grew up in Pune.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
[Guest]: So, you know, I grew up in the heart of the Deccan in that sense.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
[Guest]: Shivaji was this towering figure in all my school textbooks.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
[Guest]: But the interesting thing is that great historians have done great books on Shivaji.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.000
[Guest]: He's a figure that has been given a great deal of historical attention.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest]: But I noticed that every now and then there'd be these other characters looming behind him.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
[Guest]: And you got these cameos and occasional peep shows into their lives.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
[Guest]: But they were largely footnoted.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: So every now and then Adil Shah of Bijapur or Nizam Shah of Ahmednagar would pop up.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
[Guest]: But you never really understood who these people were.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
[Guest]: Because they were merely secondary characters in the story of Shivaji.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest]: So at some level I kept wondering who were these people.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Guest]: Because they're not Mughals. They're not South Indian.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
[Guest]: They're Shivaji's people or the people who set the stage for Shivaji to arrive.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:55.000
[Guest]: But what about their story?

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:01.000
[Guest]: So finally, you know, I kept collecting these stories in a sort of ad-hoc, non-committal fashion.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:05.000
[Guest]: But finally in 2016 when I was in Golconda in Hyderabad,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
[Guest]: I went to the Golconda fort and went and looked at the Qutub Shahi tombs there.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:13.000
[Guest]: And I was fascinated because beautiful structures, a very impressive fort.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: And strangely enough, you know, nobody seemed to know very much about it.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest]: Other than the tour guides there and a not very impressive trickle of tourists.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
[Guest]: I was like, why aren't these stories out there? They need to be told.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Guest]: So that's when I decided I would sit down and do a book on the Deccan Sultans.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And then yeah, that's when the project picked up.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of go through the timeline of the book now, which is incredibly fascinating.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And your story in a sense starts in the 13th century with the Delhi Sultanate.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And I was struck by an early bit of fake news about a character

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Amit Varma]: who's not really a character in your book at all.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:44.000
[Amit Varma]: But you sort of mentioned him early on, which is Ghiyasuddin Balban.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And Balban had never actually conquered South India or even been there or whatever.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Amit Varma]: But he got a Sanskrit inscription commissioned, which basically said,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Amit Varma]: quote, he issued forth on a military expedition.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
[Amit Varma]: The Gaudas abdicated their glory.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Amit Varma]: The Andhras, through fear, besought the shelter of the caves.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
[Amit Varma]: The Keralas forsook their pleasures.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
[Amit Varma]: The Karnatas hid themselves in defiles.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
[Amit Varma]: The Maharashtras gave their place.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
[Amit Varma]: The Gujaras resigned their vigor.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And the Lathas dwarfed themselves into Kiratas.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's, you know, just as an early example of fake news.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And there are like sort of examples of fake news throughout your book.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, you have one of his near contemporaries, Ramchandra Yadav.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
[Amit Varma]: With breathtaking humility, you mentioned, he compares himself

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Amit Varma]: to the mythological great boar in suckering the earth from the oppressions of the Turukas,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:37.000
[Amit Varma]: which is, of course, the Turks.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
[Guest]: And he never encountered a Turk.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:39.000
[Guest]: Never seen a Turk till then.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:40.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So your book immediately humanizes this by, you know,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
[Amit Varma]: placing it in a context that even we can understand today immediately.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
[Guest]: So the thing is, you know, Indian kings had this habit.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
[Guest]: It was part of an old Sanskritic tradition,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
[Guest]: which is that you draw your legitimacy,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Guest]: A, by connecting yourself to old institutions, temples,

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
[Guest]: previous dynasties sometimes.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
[Guest]: But also by these exaggerated declarations,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
[Guest]: normally in these classical languages.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Guest]: So although Balban is the Sultan of the Delhi Sultanate,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:05.000
[Guest]: he's writing in Sanskrit here.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
[Guest]: And the funny thing is a little later,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
[Guest]: you have the emperor of Vijayanagar making the same claims

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
[Guest]: about North Indian people he's never seen.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
[Guest]: Even in Shivaji's time, you have similar claims,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Guest]: where even the Madras rulers, which is essentially the British,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:17.000
[Guest]: even they're included in inscriptions,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
[Guest]: as though everybody's running away at the sight of Shivaji's armies.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Guest]: The idea is kings try to project this supernatural power,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
[Guest]: because that's how kingship was constructed in India.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
[Guest]: The idea was, it was pointless if you merely had power.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
[Guest]: Power had to be demonstrated.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
[Guest]: How? Through great rituals, through great processions.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: Why do we have this great love of processions and display?

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:37.000
[Guest]: Exactly this.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: If you had power, you had to show it.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
[Guest]: Why is it that Mughal emperors had to appear at that window

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: in the fort every day?

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
[Guest]: Because otherwise, if you didn't appear consistently for a few days,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
[Guest]: people thought you were dead.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.000
[Guest]: Which meant what? Chaos.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
[Guest]: You don't know who the next ruler is going to be.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
[Guest]: So power had to be demonstrated.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
[Guest]: These inscriptions essentially do the same thing,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
[Guest]: where they're trying to project to the elites that,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
[Guest]: oh my God, look at my influence.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
[Guest]: All these people bow before me.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:00.000
[Guest]: They may not necessarily.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: It's not completely true.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:03.000
[Guest]: But it's a way of sort of suggesting that,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
[Guest]: look, I am the most potent of them all.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest]: I am the one who dominates the landscape.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest]: Your subjects don't know better,

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Guest]: because their lives are fairly localized.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.000
[Guest]: But when you make this claim,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
[Guest]: you sort of elevate yourself to this degree,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
[Guest]: where you're special, your power becomes then unquestioned.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:21.000
[Guest]: And you know, you go into a league of great rulers and emperors and others.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:23.000
[Guest]: And people are also imitating previous rulers.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.000
[Guest]: So each of these inscriptions is imitating a previous inscription.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
[Guest]: Which is why every dynasty, every area of this country,

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Guest]: when it comes to the Sanskrit language and these common themes,

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
[Guest]: you find similar sort of bombastic, flamboyant claims,

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.000
[Guest]: because they're all trying to look impressive and over majestic.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is obviously before the age of mass media.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, this signaling that is happening,

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
[Amit Varma]: is happening for a very limited audience.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And part of that audience might be the emperor himself,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
[Guest]: or whoever the person is.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
[Guest]: I mean, it's almost like, you know, you want to look at it this way.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
[Guest]: You're a small minority of Muslim elites,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Guest]: ruling over a largely Hindu territory.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Guest]: One way of convincing yourself that you have the power,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:01.000
[Guest]: is by repeating it constantly.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
[Guest]: Even the British were no less.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
[Guest]: Even they had a similar habit of these, you know, bombastic proclamations.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: You know, Queen Victoria's proclamation was built up into this big hoo-ha.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
[Guest]: But really, how many people in villages knew who Queen Victoria was,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest]: or what she was saying?

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.000
[Guest]: Nobody did.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
[Guest]: Why did the British build these grand monuments?

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
[Guest]: Because buildings were trying to convey the idea,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.000
[Guest]: project majesty and power,

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
[Guest]: which they may not necessarily have had.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
[Guest]: So all of this goes into that fiction of power.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:29.000
[Guest]: The idea that, you know, the more I say it, the more it becomes real.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
[Guest]: The more the chances that people start taking this seriously.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
[Guest]: Because otherwise, frankly, the reality of these kings, as I said,

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
[Guest]: is that they were pretty much human like us.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
[Guest]: But if the people knew you were human, then hold on,

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:40.000
[Guest]: why are we listening to you?

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:41.000
[Guest]: Why are we your obedient subjects?

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
[Guest]: You have to make yourself special.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
[Guest]: In The Ivory Throne, I have this,

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Guest]: what I found a very fascinating episode where

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Guest]: the king, Marthanda Varma, he's created this new kingdom of Travancore in Kerala

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
[Guest]: by conquering a whole lot of places.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
[Guest]: And till then, he's first among equals.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Guest]: You know, first among all the nobles.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.000
[Guest]: In his early career, a lot of the nobles were trying to kill him.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
[Guest]: But suddenly he realizes that you have to elevate royal blood to a very special degree

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest]: so that, you know, even spilling royal blood becomes a sin.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:09.000
[Guest]: How does he do it?

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: He goes to this old Sanskritic ritual called Hiranyagarbha

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
[Guest]: where they essentially get a golden cow.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Guest]: They construct a cow made of gold.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
[Guest]: And the Raja goes in from the mouth of the cow.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Guest]: He's essentially just a regular warrior.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
[Guest]: He sits inside the cow for a certain duration.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
[Guest]: Brahmins pelt it with flowers and things to sort of,

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
[Guest]: and chant mantras of birth.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
[Guest]: And then he pops out from under the tail of the cow

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.000
[Guest]: and he's considered reborn.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
[Guest]: He's suddenly descended from the sun and the moon

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Guest]: and Suryavamshi, whatever you want.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
[Guest]: And he becomes a twice-born Kshatriya

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
[Guest]: who can wear a sacred thread and all of that.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:41.000
[Guest]: It's a second birth, but it's also a birth that's elevating him from everybody else.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:42.000
[Guest]: Now nobody else may touch him.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
[Guest]: Nobody else may eat with him.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.000
[Guest]: Only Brahmins can eat with him.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:48.000
[Guest]: So by doing that, he slowly starts elevating his thing.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
[Guest]: Every time a member of the family goes out,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Guest]: there's a procession attending to them.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
[Guest]: All of this is visually reinforcing the idea

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
[Guest]: that this family or this dynasty is special.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.000
[Guest]: So these inscriptions, these kings, their recordings, their sayings,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
[Guest]: they're all exaggerated to a degree

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
[Guest]: because all of them are trying to cement power.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
[Guest]: At the end of the day, everyone knows power comes and goes.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.000
[Guest]: If all these claims were true, these dynasties would have never fallen.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
[Guest]: Why is it that every dynasty falls

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
[Guest]: and then the next dynasty makes the same claims?

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:16.000
[Guest]: Because they're all trying to show up as much power as possible.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:19.000
[Guest]: And like today, propaganda, PR, it all matters.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest]: We still in our own times have a prime minister

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
[Guest]: who has a habit of saying things that don't always add up

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:25.000
[Guest]: when you look at the facts.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
[Guest]: But the idea is, you know, what you say matters.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
[Guest]: The image you project,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
[Guest]: the potency you can show yourself as possessing,

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:32.000
[Guest]: all of that matters.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[Guest]: And this is what they were trying to do at that time.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's fascinating to think about modern ways

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.000
[Amit Varma]: of signaling the same things.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I can't see our prime minister

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
[Amit Varma]: entering the mouth of a cow, literally.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But he's worshipping cows in other ways.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
[Amit Varma]: So your narrative really starts get going,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
[Amit Varma]: let's say around 1290 when Balban's dynasty is wiped out

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
[Amit Varma]: and the Khiljis come to power and the nephew

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.000
[Amit Varma]: of first Khilji Sultan, Alauddin is sent down south.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So let's start then.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.000
[Guest]: He actually comes down south partly for his own ambition,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
[Guest]: which is that he, you know, he realizes the south has wealth.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
[Guest]: Now they've got most of the north in their hand now.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.000
[Amit Varma]: And if I may interrupt, you also point out that

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:08.000
[Amit Varma]: legend suggests that he left court to get as far away as he could

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Amit Varma]: from a nagging wife and overbearing mother-in-law.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
[Guest]: What sources give you this?

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
[Guest]: You know, you can read about in Ferishta

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:16.000
[Guest]: and a bunch of other places.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest]: The idea again though is that,

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
[Guest]: so every time you have a historical source,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
[Guest]: you have to interrogate it for multiple things.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.000
[Guest]: Who's written it?

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:24.000
[Guest]: What is the intended audience?

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.000
[Guest]: What is the language?

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.000
[Guest]: And what is it achieving?

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
[Guest]: So, you know, if it's written in Persian,

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
[Guest]: it's not for your lay reader on the ground.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.000
[Guest]: It's not for the average peasant.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
[Guest]: It's again targeting a certain elite.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.000
[Guest]: Now when making this claim that he was only trying to get away

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
[Guest]: from a mother-in-law and just happened to come down south

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
[Guest]: and, you know, conquer a kingdom.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.000
[Guest]: All of this is trying to sort of build up a parallel narrative.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
[Guest]: In reality, the man knew exactly what he was doing.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
[Guest]: He knew there was wealth in the south.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
[Guest]: The thing is, look, the Khiljis are a new dynasty, right?

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
[Guest]: Which means they haven't been cemented in power yet.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Guest]: So if he topples his uncle, he can quickly claim power.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:57.000
[Guest]: And therefore, he needs money to bribe nobles,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
[Guest]: to get people onto his side.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
[Guest]: So for an independent source of wealth,

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:02.000
[Guest]: he needs to come south

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.000
[Guest]: because the north is entirely in his uncle's hands.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
[Guest]: Where can he get independent wealth and money and gold?

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:07.000
[Guest]: In the south.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.000
[Guest]: So the Yadavas may be writing poetry about how the Turks

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
[Guest]: and the Muslims are shivering at the thought of them.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:13.000
[Guest]: But they've never actually seen a Turk.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
[Guest]: And when Al-Awwadun shows up,

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:16.000
[Guest]: they're completely ill-prepared

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
[Guest]: because their own armies are in the south

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.000
[Guest]: fighting with the Hoysalas.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:22.000
[Guest]: And the king of the Yadavas, Ramachandra,

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
[Guest]: essentially locks himself up in the fort,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
[Guest]: but very quickly realizes that he has an impregnable fort,

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:28.000
[Guest]: but he has no food.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
[Guest]: So finally, he comes to terms with Al-Awwadun.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
[Guest]: And just then, his son comes back from the south with his army.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:34.000
[Guest]: And there you have another...

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:35.000
[Guest]: It's not fake news as such,

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.000
[Guest]: but it's a very clever strategy where

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
[Guest]: Al-Awwadun Khilji realizes he's outnumbered

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
[Guest]: and sends a bunch of horsemen into the distance

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest]: to just, you know, trot about on this distant field for a bit

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:47.000
[Guest]: so that so much dust is raised,

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
[Guest]: it starts looking like a big army is coming to aid him.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:50.000
[Guest]: And the Yadavas are horrified.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:53.000
[Guest]: They think there's some massive imperial army coming from the north.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:56.000
[Guest]: And they come to terms with Al-Awwadun Khilji

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
[Guest]: who then happily walks away from Devagiri

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
[Guest]: with heaps and mountains of gold

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
[Guest]: and takes it to the north, topples his uncle

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.000
[Guest]: and becomes the next sultan.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, when you're talking about that tactical maneuver

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
[Amit Varma]: where he had his thousand horsemen

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
[Amit Varma]: raise such a whirl of dust in the distance

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.000
[Amit Varma]: that the Yadavas believe this inspired Gannad,

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
[Amit Varma]: you also have a really nice sentence

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
[Amit Varma]: which gives a taste of the book to the reader.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Quote, and so it was that a ghost army

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
[Amit Varma]: behind a blur of earth and wind

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
[Amit Varma]: brought Devagiri to its knees.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And Devagiri, of course, is the capital of the Yadavas

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
[Amit Varma]: which later becomes Zolatabad.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:30.000
[Amit Varma]: As you point out, lay a scene for me

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
[Amit Varma]: at the time that Khilji goes to the Deccan.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
[Amit Varma]: There are essentially three sort of ruling kingdoms

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
[Amit Varma]: or dynasties or whatever

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Amit Varma]: which eventually vanish very fast within the next 50 years.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But just sort of tell us a little bit about

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
[Guest]: what those three are.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
[Guest]: So that's why I've chosen this particular period

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.000
[Guest]: for rebel sultans which is, you know,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
[Guest]: it begins in the 1290s

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.000
[Guest]: and it ends with the fall of these sultanates

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:54.000
[Guest]: in the late 17th century, in the 1680s.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.000
[Guest]: And what's interesting is that this is the Islamic period

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:58.000
[Guest]: that we have in the Deccan.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
[Guest]: Because before Khilji shows up,

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
[Guest]: what you have in what is primarily the Maharashtra region

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:05.000
[Guest]: is the Yadavas ruling from Devagiri.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.000
[Guest]: In Karnataka it's the Hoysalas

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
[Guest]: and then in Telangana you have the Kakatiyas.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.000
[Guest]: And these three dynasties are old,

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
[Guest]: they have their own claims of Sanskritic glory and so on.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
[Guest]: And they are all fighting each other obviously.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
[Amit Varma]: So the Kakatiyas are in Warangal,

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:19.000
[Amit Varma]: the Hoysalas are based in Dwarsamudra.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
[Amit Varma]: For the modern Indian,

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
[Amit Varma]: just give a context of what these areas would be.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:26.000
[Guest]: So yeah, I'd say you can basically overlap them

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
[Guest]: with modern day Karnataka for the Hoysalas,

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
[Guest]: Telangana for the Kakatiyas

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
[Guest]: and then Maharashtra for the Yadavas.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
[Guest]: Because by this time you also see the evolution of these languages.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:37.000
[Guest]: You see Karnataka, you know, building up Karnataka

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:40.000
[Guest]: and a sort of, you know, common Karnataka identity

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.000
[Guest]: through language.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
[Guest]: In Maharashtra you see the Marathi language

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: evolving at the same time.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:48.000
[Guest]: And Telanganas had this long-standing culture as well of their own.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
[Guest]: And the Kakatiyas are particularly interesting

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:55.000
[Guest]: because I mentioned these bombastic Sanskritic inscriptions and so on.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
[Guest]: One place where this sort of Sanskritism is conspicuous

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
[Guest]: in its absence is in the Kakatiya dynasty

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:03.000
[Guest]: where with one exception all the kings embraced

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:04.000
[Guest]: what is called Shudra status.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
[Guest]: They didn't want to be twice born,

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
[Guest]: sacred thread wearing Sanskritic Kshatriyas.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
[Guest]: They were more than happy being Shudras.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
[Guest]: Richard Eaton's fascinating research on how

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:15.000
[Guest]: most of the nobles in the last Kakatiya king,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:19.000
[Guest]: they hadn't inherited their place at court through the logic of blood.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:20.000
[Guest]: They'd actually worked for it.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
[Guest]: There was upward mobility that was possible.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:25.000
[Guest]: There were great public works that the Kakatiyas had installed in Telangana.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:28.000
[Guest]: So it's very interesting how each kingdom has its own flavor.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.000
[Guest]: Each was of course phenomenally wealthy.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
[Guest]: And one big reason was that these are all peninsular kingdoms.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:38.000
[Guest]: So a difference is that in the north where an empire means great size,

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:41.000
[Guest]: in the south you don't necessarily need to be that large to be of equal wealth

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:44.000
[Guest]: because being in the peninsula you have trade

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:47.000
[Guest]: which the north also has trade of course but in a very different way.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
[Guest]: When you have seaports you have another source of income

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
[Guest]: which northern empires don't have.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:54.000
[Guest]: So northern empires also realized that as you come further south

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:57.000
[Guest]: you get access to these additional sources of revenue.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:59.000
[Guest]: You get ports, you get trade and so on.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Guest]: So these southern kingdoms existed in a little cocoon of their own.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
[Guest]: They knew what was happening in the north.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:08.000
[Guest]: They knew that Islamic power had been established in Delhi and the surroundings there.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:11.000
[Guest]: But they didn't quite realize that they were going to come for them as such.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:15.000
[Guest]: I mean it wasn't, you know, we can now say that India we have these particular boundaries.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
[Guest]: In those days these boundaries didn't exist.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:21.000
[Guest]: The north was as alien then as you know we may today find Afghanistan alien.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
[Amit Varma]: It was just as different as that.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's easy to say with hindsight that, you know,

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:28.000
[Amit Varma]: had these three kingdoms sort of stayed united and fought together

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:29.000
[Amit Varma]: they could have prevailed.

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:32.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean the same criticism that you later make of the rebel sultans

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.000
[Amit Varma]: that it's only when, you know, they are split up and on different sides

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
[Amit Varma]: that they kind of fall apart.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.000
[Amit Varma]: But these guys didn't have that early lesson.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Like one of Alauddin's dreaded generals was Malik Kafur

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and the Yadavas actually helped Malik Kafur fight the Kakatiyas.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest]: Because, you know, as I said there was no,

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:51.000
[Guest]: for people who try to project nationalism and these sentiments to the past

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:55.000
[Guest]: it's unhistorical for the simple reason that people didn't see it that way.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
[Guest]: In the past power was held by a series of elite interests

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:01.000
[Guest]: that wasn't held in the name of any grand nationalistic ideology

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:04.000
[Guest]: which meant that, you know, okay we've now come to terms

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:07.000
[Guest]: that guy is still my enemy let's go eat him for breakfast together.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
[Guest]: So, you know, that sort of mentality was there

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
[Guest]: which is why after the Yadavas were taken

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.000
[Guest]: they are the ones who showed the way to the other kingdoms in the south

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:17.000
[Guest]: to Warangal and to Hoysalas because they knew that these were my enemies.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.000
[Guest]: Why should I suffer alone?

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Guest]: You know, let's try and destabilize them as well.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest]: So, on the one hand the Yadavas are trying also to kick off the northern yoke.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Guest]: They don't want to be under the Delhi sultans.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: But while the Delhi army is there

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.000
[Guest]: let's also use them to get rid of our own ancestral enemies.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's a fascinating nugget here that, you know,

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:36.000
[Amit Varma]: when Mohammed bin Tughlaq comes into the peace later on

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:39.000
[Amit Varma]: and there's a cousin of his who's fighting with him

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.000
[Amit Varma]: who takes refuge with the Hoysalas

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
[Amit Varma]: and I just want to quote this full paragraph because it's fantastic.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Amit Varma]: The Sultan ordered the prisoner to be skinned alive

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and as his skin was torn off, his flesh was cooked with rice.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Some was sent to his children and his wife

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and the remainder was put into a great dish and given to the elephants to eat.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:01.000
[Amit Varma]: The elephants, we know reassuringly, refused to touch this ghastly offering

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:04.000
[Amit Varma]: but the wail of the poor widow can only be imagined.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Her husband's skin was stuffed with straw and exhibited through the country

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:12.000
[Amit Varma]: as a lesson for all who might harbor romantic notions about resisting the Sultan

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:16.000
[Amit Varma]: in the name of their own glory or to satisfy their own ambitions."

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.000
[Amit Varma]: These were pretty gruesome times, weren't they?

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.000
[Guest]: I mean, power and violence went hand in hand at that time.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
[Guest]: You know, this often happens on Twitter

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.000
[Guest]: where people selectively pull out a random Muslim Sultan

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:29.000
[Guest]: saying, so barbaric, so violent.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
[Guest]: And like, hold on, everybody was violent at this time.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:34.000
[Guest]: It wasn't the monopoly of one faith or one set of people

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
[Guest]: because in those days, if you wanted to have power,

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
[Guest]: you had to be willing to shed blood.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
[Guest]: So, you know, for everybody who says,

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
[Guest]: oh, the Mughals killed their brothers to claim power.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.000
[Guest]: I'm sorry, that happened in Vijayanagar also.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.000
[Guest]: A brother killed a brother, a son killed a father.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.000
[Guest]: That happened in Vijayanagar.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:52.000
[Guest]: Devaraya II, one of the most charismatic and famous Vijayanagar emperors

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.000
[Guest]: had a coup either orchestrated by a nephew or a cousin.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.000
[Guest]: The exact relationship was not clear, but a close family member.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
[Guest]: In the end, Devaraya survives.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.000
[Guest]: But what does he do?

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
[Guest]: He cuts his head off, gets it in his hand

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
[Guest]: and rides a horse across the capital

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:08.000
[Guest]: just to show people that I'm still alive and my enemy is gone.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
[Guest]: That blood, the gore, it was all very natural at the time

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
[Guest]: because as I said, if you wanted to hold on to your power,

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.000
[Guest]: you had to be willing to, you know,

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.000
[Guest]: rip off people's heads and do these gruesome things.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
[Guest]: And sometimes the gruesome things were done also to make,

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
[Guest]: to sort of establish a lesson for others

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
[Guest]: who might have such similar notions,

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:27.000
[Guest]: which was that if you do this, the punishment will not be kind.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
[Guest]: You will not be comfortably poisoned to death or anything.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
[Amit Varma]: It will be painful. It will be slow.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:32.000
[Amit Varma]: The chilling effect.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:33.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in that whole Devaraya incident,

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
[Amit Varma]: where his cousin or uncle, whoever it is,

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:38.000
[Amit Varma]: he sets that up, like before he goes to Devaraya,

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:41.000
[Amit Varma]: you describe the scene, which is right out of Game of Thrones.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
[Amit Varma]: He has this elaborate banquet at his house

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and he calls all the people close to Devaraya

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:49.000
[Amit Varma]: and there's a beating of drums and there is a lot of noise there

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:52.000
[Amit Varma]: so that, you know, people can't really hear much.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And then one by one at different times,

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
[Amit Varma]: because they're supposed to have dinner at different times,

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.000
[Amit Varma]: according to their, this thing,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
[Amit Varma]: they're taken into the eating room and they're ritually slaughtered.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And after a sufficient number of them have been slaughtered,

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
[Amit Varma]: he actually goes to Devaraya and tries to do it there

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and gets beheaded for his efforts.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, at multiple points through the book,

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:13.000
[Amit Varma]: you talk about people being trampled to death by mad elephants,

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:14.000
[Amit Varma]: which is fascinating.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
[Guest]: So you don't just put them to death.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:19.000
[Guest]: And you figure out like really creative ways.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:20.000
[Guest]: Everything is a scene.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:22.000
[Guest]: Everything has to be done in public

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:26.000
[Guest]: and everything has to be done in as powerful a way as possible

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:27.000
[Guest]: so that the message goes out.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
[Guest]: Don't come and, you know, fiddle with me

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
[Guest]: because you will pay and pay badly.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
[Guest]: Because as I said, power at this time,

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.000
[Guest]: although these inscriptions make all these claims,

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:36.000
[Guest]: as we were discussing earlier,

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.000
[Guest]: it's actually very volatile.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
[Guest]: You have to have the right number of allies,

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.000
[Guest]: you have to have the right number of nobles on your side,

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:43.000
[Guest]: the right number of horses,

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.000
[Guest]: the right number of artillerymen.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:46.000
[Guest]: If you don't have all this,

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
[Guest]: your power starts very quickly going.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:49.000
[Guest]: See, even at this time,

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:50.000
[Guest]: there were no fixed borders either.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:52.000
[Guest]: So, for example, you often find that there were,

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:56.000
[Guest]: for example, Maratha, you know, Deshmukhs or village heads

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
[Guest]: in border territories.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
[Guest]: And one season they may ally with this king on this side.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
[Guest]: You may find that next year he's allying with the other king.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.000
[Guest]: So the border is constantly shifting.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.000
[Guest]: How many power interests you can keep on your side

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:08.000
[Guest]: determine your power.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:09.000
[Guest]: And fear is a great weapon.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
[Guest]: And fear is a very important asset there

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
[Guest]: because if they fear you,

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:14.000
[Guest]: then they'll listen to you.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:15.000
[Guest]: If you have money,

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:16.000
[Guest]: then they will listen to you.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
[Guest]: And finally, you have to have some claims to legitimacy.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:19.000
[Guest]: And if you don't,

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
[Guest]: you have to invent these claims to legitimacy.

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:22.000
[Guest]: So even the rebel sultans,

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
[Guest]: when they all broke off from Delhi

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.000
[Guest]: and the Delhi sultans and established their own power,

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:28.000
[Guest]: they're all scrambling for legitimacy.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[Guest]: And this isn't merely the Islamic kings.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:31.000
[Guest]: The Hindu kings do the same.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
[Guest]: So Vijayanagara tries to concoct,

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.000
[Guest]: find its own legitimacy

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
[Guest]: by concocting relationships with previous dynasties.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:38.000
[Guest]: So you know,

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
[Guest]: the early emperors are claimed to be

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.000
[Guest]: through marriage related to the Hoysalas

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:43.000
[Guest]: or you know,

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.000
[Guest]: some connection with Telangana is also found.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:48.000
[Guest]: In fact, one of the most enduring stories

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:50.000
[Guest]: is that the founders of Vijayanagara

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:51.000
[Guest]: were actually captured,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:52.000
[Guest]: taken to Delhi,

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:53.000
[Guest]: converted to Islam.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
[Guest]: And then when they came back to the south,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:56.000
[Guest]: they sort of threw off that

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:57.000
[Guest]: and went back to being Hindus.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
[Guest]: But that's why Vidyaranya, the sage,

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:01.000
[Guest]: advised them to sort of

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.000
[Guest]: rule in the name of Virupaksha, their deity.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.000
[Guest]: Because that would take away the taint of having converted.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:06.000
[Guest]: What is it trying to do?

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.000
[Guest]: Claiming legitimacy.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:08.000
[Guest]: The Sultans,

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
[Guest]: they were all trying to get legitimacy.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
[Guest]: The later Sultans from the Persian Shah,

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:13.000
[Guest]: because the Persian Shah was a superior force,

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:15.000
[Guest]: or from one of the Caliphs of Islam.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:16.000
[Guest]: Because by doing this,

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.000
[Guest]: you find a way to

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:20.000
[Guest]: get your stamp recognized as legal.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:21.000
[Guest]: Otherwise, you know,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.000
[Guest]: if you have the right number of forces,

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:24.000
[Guest]: anybody can take power.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:25.000
[Guest]: Even Shivaji, you know,

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
[Guest]: after he conquered and built his initial

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:28.000
[Guest]: Samraj as it were,

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:30.000
[Guest]: his Hindavi Swaraj,

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:31.000
[Guest]: what happens is that

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.000
[Guest]: he also goes for an elaborate coronation ceremony.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:35.000
[Guest]: He also acquires the sacred thread.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
[Guest]: He also remarries all his wives

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:39.000
[Guest]: using Sanskritic rituals.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:40.000
[Guest]: All of it is doing what?

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:42.000
[Guest]: He is connecting himself to an older tradition

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:43.000
[Guest]: and legitimizing his conquests.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:45.000
[Guest]: Till then, everybody can treat him as a warlord.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
[Guest]: But having gone through the coronation,

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
[Guest]: he becomes a legitimate king.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.000
[Guest]: And he himself in a letter notes how

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.000
[Guest]: after the coronation when he met the Kutub Shah,

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
[Guest]: the Kutub Shah would earlier expect Shivaji

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.000
[Guest]: to sort of do this prostration

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:58.000
[Guest]: like everybody else in front of him.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
[Guest]: But once Shivaji had gone through these rituals,

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
[Guest]: he was received as an equal.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.000
[Guest]: So all of this was again an effort to legitimize.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
[Guest]: And violence was also an instrument for this.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
[Guest]: Upindar Singh has written about violence in India.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:12.000
[Guest]: It's a book spanning several thousand years.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:14.000
[Guest]: And you find that violence was always there.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
[Guest]: It's only now that we can sit in times

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:18.000
[Guest]: and think that violence was sparingly used

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:20.000
[Guest]: or whatever because that's what we know.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:22.000
[Guest]: But back in the day, violence was ubiquitous.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:23.000
[Guest]: It was everywhere.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:24.000
[Guest]: It had to be everywhere.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:27.000
[Guest]: Otherwise, even your remote local sense of power,

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:28.000
[Guest]: being a village head or whatever,

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.000
[Guest]: everything depended on how many swords you had.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of get back to Khilji for a moment

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:36.000
[Amit Varma]: on how Khilji basically over a period of time,

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.000
[Amit Varma]: not Khilji per se himself alone,

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:40.000
[Amit Varma]: but these three started the process

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:43.000
[Amit Varma]: by which these three empires got wiped out in the south.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.000
[Guest]: So he comes to the south.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
[Guest]: He obviously gets all the money from Devagiri

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:48.000
[Guest]: and then goes back.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:51.000
[Guest]: It's his eunuch lover Malik Afur

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
[Guest]: who eventually comes and finishes the job

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
[Guest]: by one by one picking off these kingdoms

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:56.000
[Guest]: and taking over.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:59.000
[Guest]: And what you then find is that these Hindu kingdoms

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:00.000
[Guest]: or empires, whatever you will,

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
[Guest]: they start folding and collapsing

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.000
[Guest]: and various either local powers emerge,

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:06.000
[Guest]: which is that when there's a vacuum,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.000
[Guest]: other ambitious people locally will emerge to claim it

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:10.000
[Guest]: or sometimes as you have in Madurai,

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.000
[Guest]: a new Muslim Sultanate emerged there

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:15.000
[Guest]: because one problem the Delhi Sultans faced consistently

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.000
[Guest]: while they had any influence in the south

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:19.000
[Guest]: was that they would send nobles to the south

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:20.000
[Guest]: but the distance was so large

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:22.000
[Guest]: that these nobles are too often tempted to rebel

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:25.000
[Guest]: and sort of establish their own independent kingdoms.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:27.000
[Guest]: So the guy sent off to Madurai decided,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:28.000
[Guest]: why am I paying tribute to Delhi?

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.000
[Guest]: I'm so far away.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:31.000
[Guest]: I can become an independent Sultan.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:32.000
[Guest]: So he does that.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.000
[Guest]: You know, people often present Vijayanagar

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.000
[Guest]: as a dharmic Hindu cause.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:38.000
[Guest]: Well, then they would have prevented the Hoysalas

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:39.000
[Guest]: and the other dynasties from falling.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:40.000
[Guest]: No.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:42.000
[Guest]: They also took advantage of the fall of these kingdoms.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:43.000
[Guest]: They didn't stall them.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
[Guest]: They merely made sure that as these kingdoms were falling,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.000
[Amit Varma]: they were occupying the vacuum that came.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:48.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, as I think you pointed out,

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
[Amit Varma]: the five brothers who founded the Vijayanagar kingdom

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:52.000
[Amit Varma]: were also claiming legitimacy

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
[Amit Varma]: by claiming to be descended from the previous kingdoms

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:55.000
[Guest]: and so on.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.000
[Guest]: They all had various ways of, you know,

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:00.000
[Guest]: trying to make their conquests look as legal as possible.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:01.000
[Guest]: But what they were all doing,

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.000
[Guest]: what Alauddin Khilji essentially did was

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.000
[Guest]: he destabilized this entire region.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:06.000
[Guest]: Everything started falling.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:08.000
[Guest]: And once these existing powers fell,

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:09.000
[Guest]: it became a free-for-all.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.000
[Guest]: Anybody who had the capacity could build something new.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.000
[Guest]: As it happened in the northern Deccan,

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
[Guest]: it was the Bamani Sultanate that eventually emerged.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.000
[Guest]: In the southern Deccan, it was Vijayanagar that emerged.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.000
[Guest]: And then these two entities were locked in conflict

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.000
[Amit Varma]: constantly with each other.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
[Amit Varma]: What would enable this was also, you know,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:26.000
[Amit Varma]: a classic, the blunder by Tughlaq.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we remember Tughlaq for the shift to Daulatabad in 1327,

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:31.000
[Amit Varma]: which of course was a blunder

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:34.000
[Amit Varma]: and the army had to kind of go back after a while.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And even this is told very entertainingly by you

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.000
[Amit Varma]: because you write about how he forced all of Delhi

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:40.000
[Amit Varma]: to shift to Daulatabad

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:42.000
[Amit Varma]: and this included a blind man who didn't want to go.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And he was actually dragged to Daulatabad.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:46.000
[Amit Varma]: So he started losing his limbs.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And when he actually reached Daulatabad,

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:49.000
[Amit Varma]: he had only one leg.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:50.000
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a, it's an,

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:51.000
[Guest]: I'm pretty sure it's an apocryphal story,

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:52.000
[Guest]: but it's an entertaining one.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:53.000
[Guest]: The idea being, this is,

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
[Guest]: this is one chronicler's way of saying that

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
[Guest]: this was how drastic the move was.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:58.000
[Guest]: I'm pretty sure this didn't happen

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.000
[Guest]: because whoever was pulling would have realized

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
[Guest]: that the man was falling away in bits on the way.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
[Guest]: But the idea was that, you know,

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.000
[Amit Varma]: everybody had to move.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's absolutely fantastic.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:09.000
[Amit Varma]: But the real blunder was in 1345,

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.000
[Amit Varma]: what Tughlaq kind of did was that

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:14.000
[Amit Varma]: he recalled his old guard governor from Daulatabad

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
[Amit Varma]: and there was now this internecine battle

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:17.000
[Amit Varma]: between the old guard,

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
[Amit Varma]: whom he was trying to get rid of

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
[Amit Varma]: with these new people

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
[Guest]: who he thought would be loyal to him.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:24.000
[Guest]: So he, what he did was,

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.000
[Guest]: because all these people going to the south

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.000
[Guest]: were too readily tempted to sort of

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
[Guest]: stand up in rebellion and claim independence,

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
[Guest]: he thought he would create a new aristocracy

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
[Guest]: who would be personally loyal to them.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
[Guest]: So of course you have a critic of this saying

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
[Guest]: that cooks and cobblers and everybody's sons

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
[Guest]: were overnight turned into noblemen

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:42.000
[Guest]: and then the old guard was expected

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:43.000
[Guest]: to relinquish power to them.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.000
[Guest]: Now this could also be a legitimizing trick

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:46.000
[Guest]: for the old guard

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
[Guest]: because they ended up breaking away from Delhi.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:49.000
[Guest]: So they made it look like,

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
[Guest]: oh look, we are the legitimate ones.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
[Guest]: This king is bringing low born people to power

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:54.000
[Guest]: which is not correct

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:55.000
[Guest]: and therefore we are breaking away

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:56.000
[Guest]: from his unjust rule.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:57.000
[Guest]: But in the end that failed

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
[Guest]: because if he tried to create a new aristocracy

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:00.000
[Guest]: it didn't work.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
[Guest]: The old aristocracy managed to hold together

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
[Guest]: and create an independent sultanate in the south

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.000
[Guest]: which was of course the Bamani Sultanate

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:08.000
[Guest]: where they ended up selecting their first sultan

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:09.000
[Guest]: almost by lottery

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:12.000
[Guest]: because they chose the most efficient among them

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:15.000
[Guest]: and he is the one who became the first Bamani Sultan.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And that was Hasan Gangu who called himself

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Abul Muzaffar Alauddin Behman Shah

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
[Amit Varma]: and there was some sort of speculation

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:26.000
[Amit Varma]: about his surname itself, Behman.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Why is he calling himself that?

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
[Guest]: People think that he was a servant to a Brahmin

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.000
[Guest]: and this was some way of commemorating

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.000
[Guest]: his original master.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
[Guest]: Another theory is that he was half Hindu

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:36.000
[Guest]: which is likely

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
[Guest]: because even the Tughlaqs took Hindu wives.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:39.000
[Guest]: So the later Tughlaqs

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
[Guest]: as you come further down the family tree

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
[Guest]: they are all essentially the sons of Hindu mothers.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:46.000
[Guest]: So it's very likely that Hasan Gangu's mother

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:47.000
[Guest]: was also Brahmin.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
[Guest]: But of course connecting Baman to Brahmin

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.000
[Guest]: is a little too convenient

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
[Guest]: and therefore it's very unlikely

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
[Guest]: this was the origin of that title.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:58.000
[Guest]: And in reality we know that he grew up in Multan.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
[Guest]: He was involved in the sultanate.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
[Guest]: He even served in Afghanistan briefly

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:03.000
[Guest]: and he had his own career.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.000
[Guest]: He was essentially a top level nobleman.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:08.000
[Guest]: He had led a botched rebellion at one time

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:11.000
[Guest]: but then when the Deccan was finally breaking away

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:12.000
[Guest]: he landed up on the scene

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:13.000
[Guest]: did a very good job

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:14.000
[Guest]: and impressed all his peers

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
[Guest]: and therefore they ended up making him sultan.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And what's interesting was that

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
[Amit Varma]: he immediately abolished Jazia long before Akbar

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:22.000
[Amit Varma]: and you point out there's possibly two reasons for this.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:23.000
[Amit Varma]: One is just real politic

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
[Amit Varma]: because he was helped in his quest to power

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
[Amit Varma]: by a bunch of Hindu chieftains.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:31.000
[Amit Varma]: So obviously he's going to want to keep him on their good side.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And two, to distinguish himself from the brutal Naudis

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
[Amit Varma]: in a manner of speaking.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And this also sort of ties back to something

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:39.000
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned in your book

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.000
[Amit Varma]: about how there are sort of two faces of Islam in India

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:46.000
[Amit Varma]: and one is you have Islam coming pre the 10th century to South India

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:47.000
[Amit Varma]: and it's very peaceful

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and there are traders

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and there are perhaps even refugees

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
[Amit Varma]: who are getting away from where they are coming from

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
[Amit Varma]: and they are immediately integrated into the culture

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and it's all very peaceful.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other is invasions from the North

00:38:58.000 --> 00:38:59.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And that struck me as pretty fascinating.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:04.000
[Guest]: Yeah, the South, you know,

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:05.000
[Guest]: this is the thing where I mentioned

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.000
[Guest]: that there is a Northern bias in Indian history

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.000
[Guest]: because if you look at everything from the North

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:10.000
[Guest]: you get one perspective

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:11.000
[Guest]: which is that Islam came to India how?

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
[Guest]: When the swords were raised in the Sindh.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
[Guest]: Now if you look at the same issue

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
[Guest]: which is Islam's arrival in India from the South

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:18.000
[Guest]: completely different perspective

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:20.000
[Guest]: because if legend is to be believed

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.000
[Guest]: the oldest mosque in Kerala

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.000
[Guest]: was built in the lifetime of the Prophet himself

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:25.000
[Guest]: one year before the Prophet dies

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.000
[Guest]: you have this mosque being established in Kodungallur.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:28.000
[Guest]: Okay, there is no proof of this

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.000
[Guest]: because the current building is not that old

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:32.000
[Guest]: but even then, two centuries later

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
[Guest]: in the 800s

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:35.000
[Guest]: you have inscriptional evidence

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
[Guest]: with Arabic signatures of Muslims

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:38.000
[Guest]: which is that Muslims are already witnessing

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
[Guest]: royal Hindu grants by this time

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
[Guest]: to have that kind of influence

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:43.000
[Guest]: they had at least been there for a hundred years

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
[Guest]: they had at least been there for a while

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:46.000
[Guest]: to have that kind of power.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.000
[Guest]: So Islam came to the South

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:49.000
[Guest]: through peaceful embassies of commerce

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.000
[Guest]: they existed all around the Konkan coast

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:54.000
[Guest]: in fact, culturally Kerala has more in common

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:56.000
[Guest]: with Arabia than it has with North India

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:57.000
[Guest]: Delhi has more in common with Kabul

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
[Guest]: than it has with South India

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
[Guest]: and this is not very convenient now

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: for people to say

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:04.000
[Guest]: because we are now sort of completely infected

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.000
[Guest]: by this over-nationalistic bug

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:08.000
[Guest]: but that's how history was

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
[Guest]: people had various links in this way

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:11.000
[Guest]: and Islam therefore

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
[Guest]: in the South wasn't a disruptive force

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
[Guest]: people associated Islam with trade

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
[Guest]: and that is how even later in these sultanates

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
[Guest]: you find that a lot of culture

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
[Guest]: came through Islamic networks

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.000
[Guest]: so even now if you go to Tirupati

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:24.000
[Guest]: there are these famous bronzes

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:26.000
[Guest]: of Krishnadevaraya and his wife

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:27.000
[Guest]: the Vijayanagara emperor and his wife

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
[Guest]: go two of them

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:30.000
[Guest]: if you look at the bronze closely

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:32.000
[Guest]: now they've draped the women in saris or whatever

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.000
[Guest]: but they haven't covered Krishnadevaraya's head

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.000
[Guest]: he's wearing a Turkish hat

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:38.000
[Guest]: because Turkish fashions became fashionable

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:39.000
[Guest]: in Vijayanagara at that time

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:40.000
[Guest]: if you go to Hampi

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:42.000
[Guest]: you'll find that early stage remains

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:44.000
[Guest]: or the ruins in Hampi

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:46.000
[Guest]: typical, everybody's wearing the South Indian

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
[Guest]: munda or the veshti or whatever

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
[Guest]: and the torso is left bare

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:51.000
[Guest]: but as time passes

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
[Guest]: you see in later structures that have survived

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
[Guest]: the tunic starts appearing

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
[Guest]: in the Vitthala temple

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
[Guest]: there's a pillar which shows an Arab or a Muslim

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:01.000
[Guest]: on a horse

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:02.000
[Guest]: and this is in a temple

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.000
[Guest]: a Muslim enshrined forever on its walls

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:05.000
[Guest]: in its pillars

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:07.000
[Guest]: at the great platform

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:09.000
[Guest]: where all the great rituals are supposedly held

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
[Guest]: you see Arabs carved into the sides

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.000
[Guest]: and they're dancing and entertaining the Vijayanagara emperor

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:14.000
[Guest]: and so on

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:15.000
[Guest]: and most striking of all is

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.000
[Guest]: from the 1350s

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.000
[Guest]: the Vijayanagara emperors adopted a new title

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
[Guest]: which was Hinduraya Suratrana

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:22.000
[Guest]: interesting for two reasons

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:25.000
[Guest]: because Suratrana is the Sanskritization of Sultan

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
[Guest]: you find it in the Delhi Sultanate

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:28.000
[Guest]: where on the coins on one hand

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.000
[Guest]: on the one side you have the Arabic Sultan

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:32.000
[Guest]: on the other hand you have Suratrana

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.000
[Guest]: in Nepal when the Sultan of Bengal invades

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:35.000
[Guest]: Suratrana

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:36.000
[Guest]: even in Shah Jahan's time

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:37.000
[Guest]: the word for Sultan

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.000
[Guest]: in Sanskrit is Suratrana

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
[Guest]: so the Vijayanagara kings are calling themselves

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:42.000
[Guest]: Hinduraya Suratrana

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
[Guest]: which is Sultans among Hindu kings

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:45.000
[Guest]: which is that

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:46.000
[Guest]: funnily enough

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
[Guest]: they're the first people I think

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:49.000
[Guest]: who are appropriating Hindu

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:51.000
[Guest]: which is a word normally outsiders use

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:52.000
[Guest]: to everybody in India

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.000
[Guest]: and applying it to themselves

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:56.000
[Guest]: so saying among Hindu kings

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:57.000
[Guest]: we are the Sultans

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:58.000
[Guest]: which is that we are Hindus

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
[Guest]: but we are also Sultans

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.000
[Guest]: you find a Telugu lord also

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:03.000
[Guest]: calling himself Suratrana

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:04.000
[Guest]: so

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:05.000
[Guest]: Islamicate culture

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.000
[Guest]: was bringing all this to the south

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:08.000
[Guest]: you know it was bringing soft power

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:09.000
[Guest]: of a certain type

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:10.000
[Guest]: fashion

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.000
[Guest]: what you were wearing

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:14.000
[Guest]: what you were eating perhaps

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:15.000
[Guest]: what you were calling yourself

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:18.000
[Guest]: everything depended on these Islamic networks

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:19.000
[Guest]: which wasn't the story of the north

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.000
[Guest]: the north had a very different

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:22.000
[Guest]: experience with Islam

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:23.000
[Guest]: but there also

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:24.000
[Guest]: you find these compromises

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:25.000
[Guest]: because

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:26.000
[Guest]: Mahmud of Ghor for example

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:27.000
[Guest]: you know famous for destroying

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
[Guest]: temples and killing so many infidels

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
[Guest]: he happily boasts that he killed

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:32.000
[Guest]: so many thousand infidels

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:33.000
[Guest]: but at the same time

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:34.000
[Guest]: in the coins he minted

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:35.000
[Guest]: he had no option

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.000
[Guest]: but to have an infidel goddess Lakshmi

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:38.000
[Guest]: because otherwise

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.000
[Guest]: the infidels would not use his coins

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:41.000
[Guest]: so the thing is

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
[Guest]: for legitimizing yourself

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
[Guest]: for audiences in the Islamic world

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:46.000
[Guest]: you play up the idea

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:47.000
[Guest]: of you bringing Islam

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
[Guest]: to these eastern barbaric lands

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:50.000
[Guest]: whereas in reality

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:51.000
[Guest]: in the so called barbaric lands

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:52.000
[Guest]: you have to come to terms

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:53.000
[Guest]: with the people

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:54.000
[Guest]: which is what happened

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:55.000
[Guest]: in the Deccan as well

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:56.000
[Guest]: you come to power

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:57.000
[Guest]: but you realize very quickly

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:58.000
[Guest]: that you are a minority

00:42:58.000 --> 00:42:59.000
[Guest]: you need local power

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.000
[Guest]: you need local assistance

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:02.000
[Guest]: that's how the Marathas emerged

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:03.000
[Guest]: as a very powerful caste

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:04.000
[Guest]: because they became

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:05.000
[Guest]: the middlemen

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.000
[Guest]: between the people on the ground

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:07.000
[Guest]: the agriculturists

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:08.000
[Guest]: and the Sultans

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:09.000
[Guest]: in the big towns and cities

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:10.000
[Guest]: because they were the ones

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:11.000
[Guest]: who knew the countryside

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:12.000
[Guest]: they were the ones

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:13.000
[Guest]: who rallied the armies

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:14.000
[Guest]: to fight for these Sultans

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:16.000
[Guest]: so the Maratha caste itself

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:17.000
[Guest]: rose to prominence

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
[Guest]: in the period of the Sultanates

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:20.000
[Guest]: because finally

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
[Guest]: they had a particular purpose

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:23.000
[Guest]: acting as the main

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
[Guest]: sort of intermediaries of power

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
[Guest]: as main brokers of power as well

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.000
[Amit Varma]: so I'm speculating here

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:30.000
[Amit Varma]: and thinking aloud

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:31.000
[Amit Varma]: this is probably very simplistic

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:32.000
[Amit Varma]: but the thought just struck me

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:33.000
[Amit Varma]: when you were speaking

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
[Amit Varma]: is that is it then possible

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that the reason

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:37.000
[Amit Varma]: that that simplistic

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Hindutva binary

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:40.000
[Amit Varma]: of Hindus good

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Muslims bad

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:42.000
[Amit Varma]: is more dominant

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:43.000
[Amit Varma]: in the North

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:44.000
[Amit Varma]: because the North

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:45.000
[Amit Varma]: has experienced Islam

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:46.000
[Amit Varma]: more in that way

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
[Guest]: I think that may be one example

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
[Guest]: because their introduction

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:51.000
[Guest]: to Islam

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:52.000
[Guest]: came through blood

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:53.000
[Guest]: and violence and war

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:54.000
[Guest]: that would lead to

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:55.000
[Guest]: a certain kind of

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:56.000
[Guest]: impression of Islam

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.000
[Guest]: in Kerala again

00:43:58.000 --> 00:43:59.000
[Guest]: to give an example

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:00.000
[Guest]: the experience is a

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:01.000
[Guest]: polar opposite

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:02.000
[Guest]: because there has been

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:03.000
[Guest]: no violence till

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:04.000
[Guest]: the Moplah rebellion

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:05.000
[Guest]: in 1921

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:06.000
[Guest]: in the previous century

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:07.000
[Guest]: in the 19th century

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:08.000
[Guest]: there were what were

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:09.000
[Guest]: called the outrages

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:10.000
[Guest]: which had a religious element

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:11.000
[Guest]: there was a so called

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:12.000
[Guest]: Jihadi element to it

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.000
[Guest]: which is fascinating

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:14.000
[Guest]: but what is interesting

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:15.000
[Guest]: is that in Kerala

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:16.000
[Guest]: the Muslims

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:17.000
[Guest]: were so deeply

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:18.000
[Guest]: wedded into

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:19.000
[Guest]: the general Hindu society

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:21.000
[Guest]: there was no Parda

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:22.000
[Guest]: the women did not have Parda

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:23.000
[Guest]: there was a matrilineal

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:24.000
[Guest]: Muslim royal family

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:25.000
[Guest]: the family of the

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:26.000
[Guest]: Arakkal Bibi

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:27.000
[Guest]: which is completely

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:28.000
[Guest]: against the Sharia

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:29.000
[Guest]: you know in the

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:30.000
[Guest]: Arakkal family

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:31.000
[Guest]: it's the eldest child

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:32.000
[Guest]: that inherits

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:33.000
[Guest]: if it's a girl

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:34.000
[Guest]: it's called the Arakkal Bibi

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:35.000
[Guest]: if it's called

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:36.000
[Guest]: it's called the Ali Raja

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:37.000
[Guest]: but the point is

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:38.000
[Guest]: women had right of succession

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:39.000
[Guest]: and this is a woman

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:40.000
[Guest]: who corresponded

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:41.000
[Guest]: with the Turkish

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:42.000
[Guest]: Ottoman Sultan

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:43.000
[Guest]: and so on

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:44.000
[Guest]: but she was the product

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:45.000
[Guest]: of a matrilineal system

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:46.000
[Guest]: which is a very

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:47.000
[Guest]: Malayali upper caste thing

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:48.000
[Guest]: it's not an Islamic concept

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:49.000
[Guest]: there is also something

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:50.000
[Guest]: called the Moplah Ramayana

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:51.000
[Guest]: or the Muslim Ramayana

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:52.000
[Guest]: in Kerala

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:53.000
[Guest]: where Shurpanakha

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:54.000
[Guest]: tries to seduce Rama

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:55.000
[Guest]: and Rama says no no

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:56.000
[Guest]: but I have already

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:57.000
[Guest]: got a wife

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:58.000
[Guest]: so they were

00:44:58.000 --> 00:44:59.000
[Guest]: very deeply wedded

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:00.000
[Guest]: to local society

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:01.000
[Guest]: just as the Christians were

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:02.000
[Guest]: you know their

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:03.000
[Guest]: oldest churches

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:04.000
[Guest]: just like the oldest

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:05.000
[Guest]: mosques in Kerala

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:06.000
[Guest]: there are no minarets

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:07.000
[Guest]: there are no domes

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:08.000
[Guest]: they are built

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:09.000
[Guest]: like Kerala structures

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:10.000
[Guest]: made of wood

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:11.000
[Guest]: with gables

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:12.000
[Guest]: and so on

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:13.000
[Guest]: and if you go to Calicut

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:14.000
[Guest]: there is something

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:15.000
[Guest]: called the Mishkal Palli

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:16.000
[Guest]: which is a mosque

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:17.000
[Guest]: built about 800 years ago

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:18.000
[Guest]: at some point

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:19.000
[Guest]: the Portuguese

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:20.000
[Guest]: come and destroy it

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:21.000
[Guest]: some 70-80 years later

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:22.000
[Guest]: in the 1570-72

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:23.000
[Guest]: I think

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:24.000
[Guest]: the Zamorin of Calicut

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:25.000
[Guest]: who is a Hindu ruler

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:26.000
[Guest]: goes to war

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:27.000
[Guest]: against the Portuguese

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:28.000
[Guest]: wins

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:29.000
[Guest]: dismantles

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:30.000
[Guest]: one of their forts

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:31.000
[Guest]: brings back all the wood

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:32.000
[Guest]: and reconstructs this mosque

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:33.000
[Guest]: that was demolished

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:34.000
[Guest]: some 70 years before

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:35.000
[Guest]: because

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:36.000
[Guest]: their identities

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:37.000
[Guest]: didn't depend on their

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:38.000
[Guest]: religious loyalties

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:39.000
[Guest]: or allegiances

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:40.000
[Guest]: they were much more than that

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:41.000
[Guest]: even the rebel Sultans

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:42.000
[Guest]: in general

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:43.000
[Guest]: the point I make is that

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:44.000
[Guest]: religion is not what

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:45.000
[Guest]: guided their politics

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:46.000
[Guest]: religion often lent

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:47.000
[Guest]: legitimacy

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:48.000
[Guest]: it often justified

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:49.000
[Guest]: what they were doing

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.000
[Guest]: but politics itself

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:51.000
[Guest]: was guided by the same

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:52.000
[Guest]: things that it is

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:53.000
[Guest]: even today guided by

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:54.000
[Guest]: which is power

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:55.000
[Guest]: greed

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:56.000
[Guest]: avarice

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:57.000
[Guest]: that sort of

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:58.000
[Amit Varma]: those human instincts

00:45:58.000 --> 00:45:59.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact religion was

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:00.000
[Amit Varma]: almost in a sense

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:01.000
