[Guest]: Bidar.

00:56:39.800 --> 00:56:41.400
[Guest]: Oh, it's still called Bidar.

00:56:41.400 --> 00:56:44.280
[Guest]: And so the idea is that he's trying to tap into all that saying that, you know, this

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:46.440
[Guest]: is an old city with very many old links.

00:56:46.440 --> 00:56:48.200
[Guest]: I'm sort of channeling that.

00:56:48.200 --> 00:56:51.640
[Guest]: But the other thing is also, as I said, these are all military states in the sense that

00:56:51.640 --> 00:56:55.080
[Guest]: you have to constantly keep replenishing your military capacity.

00:56:55.080 --> 00:56:59.160
[Guest]: For that, this importing from the West became extremely important because the best horses

00:56:59.160 --> 00:57:00.160
[Guest]: came from Persia.

00:57:00.160 --> 00:57:01.880
[Guest]: Horses do not thrive in India.

00:57:01.880 --> 00:57:03.600
[Guest]: And this is why often Vijayanagara was left behind.

00:57:03.600 --> 00:57:07.480
[Guest]: And the Vijayanagara emperors always grappled with this internal conundrum, which was that

00:57:07.480 --> 00:57:11.780
[Guest]: even though they were bigger, even though they were often wealthier than the Sultans,

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:15.040
[Guest]: they were often defeated on the battlefield simply because they didn't have the latest

00:57:15.040 --> 00:57:18.760
[Guest]: artillery technology that the Sultans imported from Turkey.

00:57:18.760 --> 00:57:20.960
[Guest]: All the artillerymen were usually Ottomans.

00:57:20.960 --> 00:57:24.680
[Guest]: They got their best horses from Persia and they got these soldiers from Persia.

00:57:24.680 --> 00:57:27.840
[Guest]: And the thing is, the idea was that by getting these foreigners in, there would be a degree

00:57:27.840 --> 00:57:28.840
[Guest]: of loyalty.

00:57:28.840 --> 00:57:32.480
[Guest]: They also got Africans, thousands and thousands of Africans who had absolutely no other loyalties.

00:57:32.480 --> 00:57:34.960
[Guest]: Their loyalties were only supposed to be to the Sultan.

00:57:34.960 --> 00:57:40.080
[Guest]: So being Muslims, the Bhamani Sultans could tap into this Islamic network that brought

00:57:40.080 --> 00:57:42.700
[Guest]: them the best of the world at the time.

00:57:42.700 --> 00:57:47.240
[Guest]: Best of technology, the best of arms and, you know, ammunition that they needed.

00:57:47.240 --> 00:57:49.840
[Guest]: And of course, the best of actual manpower.

00:57:49.840 --> 00:57:53.600
[Guest]: Whereas Vijayanagara was a little handicapped there because everything that came to them,

00:57:53.600 --> 00:57:55.000
[Guest]: first the Bhamani Sultans would have.

00:57:55.000 --> 00:57:59.540
[Guest]: So scholars have found, for example, that Vijayanagara never evolved a fortification

00:57:59.540 --> 00:58:01.880
[Guest]: technique like the northern Sultans of the Deccan.

00:58:01.880 --> 00:58:06.560
[Guest]: Because the Sultans kept upgrading their forts as, you know, upgradations happened elsewhere

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:09.200
[Guest]: in the world because the Islamic network connected them to that.

00:58:09.200 --> 00:58:13.440
[Guest]: Whereas the Vijayanagara emperors never bothered to build up their forts that way, which eventually

00:58:13.440 --> 00:58:15.360
[Guest]: they ended up paying a cost for.

00:58:15.360 --> 00:58:19.560
[Guest]: So what Ahmed Shah was also doing was this, trying to reinforce on the one hand this link

00:58:19.560 --> 00:58:24.240
[Guest]: to Persia to keep the Bhamani Sultanate within that network, on the other hand, trying to

00:58:24.240 --> 00:58:28.440
[Guest]: milk that network for whatever it was worth to get the best into his kingdom, whether

00:58:28.440 --> 00:58:30.580
[Guest]: it was people or whether it was technology.

00:58:30.580 --> 00:58:34.880
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps as a consequence of this, he then ended up defeating Vijayanagara, where he

00:58:34.880 --> 00:58:39.280
[Amit Varma]: then destroyed a lot of temples and what you call colleges of Brahmins.

00:58:39.280 --> 00:58:43.320
[Amit Varma]: And there's a very funny story about here when the battle is ongoing about how both

00:58:43.320 --> 00:58:48.720
[Amit Varma]: the leaders of the forces, Zaria of Vijayanagara and Ahmed Shah himself almost got captured

00:58:48.720 --> 00:58:49.720
[Amit Varma]: in battle.

00:58:49.720 --> 00:58:51.320
[Guest]: The story about the Raya was quite hilarious.

00:58:51.320 --> 00:58:55.520
[Guest]: Yeah, these, I mean, that again, the stories tell you that, you know, battle wasn't one

00:58:55.520 --> 00:59:00.320
[Guest]: situation, as cinema shows, you know, everybody meets on a battlefield and clashes, you know,

00:59:00.320 --> 00:59:02.040
[Guest]: huge establishments are moving.

00:59:02.040 --> 00:59:06.680
[Guest]: Often the largest section of a moving army is the cooks and the cleaners and the prostitutes

00:59:06.680 --> 00:59:09.080
[Guest]: and people like that, the bazaar that moves with it.

00:59:09.080 --> 00:59:13.600
[Guest]: So you, I had this later quote towards the end in the book about the Marathas and how

00:59:13.600 --> 00:59:17.640
[Guest]: towards the end when the Mughals moved, there'd be a soldier, his wife would be with him,

00:59:17.640 --> 00:59:20.880
[Guest]: his babies would be with him, the soldier would be carrying things on his head, his

00:59:20.880 --> 00:59:24.480
[Guest]: gun would be in the hand of his wife, and she would have stuck some kitchen ladle or

00:59:24.480 --> 00:59:26.480
[Guest]: something into the barrel of the gun.

00:59:26.480 --> 00:59:29.320
[Guest]: And suddenly out of nowhere, the Marathas will appear on horses, cut off everybody's

00:59:29.320 --> 00:59:31.160
[Guest]: head quickly and disappear into the hills.

00:59:31.160 --> 00:59:35.160
[Guest]: And before these guys could remove the ladle and start taking aim, they were dead.

00:59:35.160 --> 00:59:39.100
[Guest]: So armies on the move were also big establishments that were on the move.

00:59:39.100 --> 00:59:43.200
[Guest]: So in these situations, sometimes you have context where say the Raya is sitting somewhere,

00:59:43.200 --> 00:59:46.360
[Guest]: his tent is pitched somewhere, ends up being not protected well.

00:59:46.360 --> 00:59:50.000
[Guest]: Similarly, in this particular battle, what happens is, on the one hand, Ahmed Shah one

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:51.720
[Guest]: day decides I want to go for a hunt.

00:59:51.720 --> 00:59:55.440
[Guest]: So battle is not a one day event, it's a leisurely pace, you know, the king comes slowly, they

00:59:55.440 --> 00:59:56.440
[Guest]: set up camp.

00:59:56.440 --> 00:59:57.440
[Amit Varma]: It's a marathon not a sprint.

00:59:57.440 --> 00:59:59.040
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a very convenient thing.

00:59:59.040 --> 01:00:03.000
[Guest]: So he decides, let me go for a hunt, he ends up going too far, and ends up being ambushed

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:04.680
[Guest]: by a set of Vijayanagara people.

01:00:04.680 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest]: And he's chased till he reaches this rather unglamorous situation where this Sultan of

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:12.640
[Guest]: the Bahmanis, you know, king of so many Persians and Africans or whatever, ends up hiding in

01:00:12.640 --> 01:00:13.640
[Guest]: a barn.

01:00:13.640 --> 01:00:18.080
[Guest]: And he's luckily saved because a number of his own men come to his rescue, but he could

01:00:18.080 --> 01:00:20.000
[Guest]: have fallen into Vijayanagara's hands.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:24.840
[Guest]: Similarly, you have this Vijayanagara emperor, who's reposing somewhere in a field comfortably,

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:29.160
[Guest]: when suddenly he discovers that, you know, these Bahmani troops have come in.

01:00:29.160 --> 01:00:31.960
[Guest]: And because he's sitting there in his South Indian clothes, he's not actually dressed

01:00:31.960 --> 01:00:32.960
[Guest]: like a king.

01:00:32.960 --> 01:00:33.960
[Guest]: He's just wearing a lungi and he's sitting shirtless.

01:00:33.960 --> 01:00:34.960
[Amit Varma]: He's nearly naked.

01:00:34.960 --> 01:00:36.560
[Guest]: He's nearly naked.

01:00:36.560 --> 01:00:38.200
[Guest]: So people think he's a nobody.

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:39.840
[Guest]: He's just some random man who's lying there.

01:00:39.840 --> 01:00:44.720
[Guest]: So he gets up and they say, we're now looting the sugarcane field, here, hold these sugarcanes.

01:00:44.720 --> 01:00:48.200
[Guest]: And he sort of, the soldiers try and make him their, I don't know, their coolie for

01:00:48.200 --> 01:00:49.200
[Guest]: the day.

01:00:49.200 --> 01:00:52.040
[Guest]: And he very quietly and cleverly decides not to say that he's actually the emperor on the

01:00:52.040 --> 01:00:53.040
[Guest]: other side.

01:00:53.040 --> 01:00:56.280
[Guest]: And for some time, he's carrying the sugarcanes with them because they just think he's some

01:00:56.280 --> 01:00:57.280
[Guest]: random man.

01:00:57.280 --> 01:00:59.440
[Guest]: And of course, then they discover that the main battle has been won.

01:00:59.440 --> 01:01:01.760
[Guest]: And now there's gold to be had instead of sugarcane.

01:01:01.760 --> 01:01:03.060
[Guest]: So they abandon him and go.

01:01:03.060 --> 01:01:05.960
[Guest]: And that's how the Vijayanagara emperor ends up saving himself.

01:01:05.960 --> 01:01:10.440
[Guest]: It's the same in the final battle where Vijayanagara falls in 1565 as well, where the Vijayanagara

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:14.200
[Guest]: sultan is in a palanquin or one of those sedan chairs or whatever.

01:01:14.200 --> 01:01:18.240
[Guest]: And he ends up in the wrong place where an elephant comes from the other side.

01:01:18.240 --> 01:01:21.460
[Guest]: His bearers of his palanquin run away and he's just lying about there.

01:01:21.460 --> 01:01:24.440
[Guest]: And then an idiot Brahmin says, no, no, no, don't hurt him.

01:01:24.440 --> 01:01:26.200
[Guest]: He's the raya of Vijayanagara.

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:27.920
[Guest]: That's the only reason he was captured.

01:01:27.920 --> 01:01:30.940
[Guest]: Otherwise the elephant and the elephant rider would have moved on thinking he was just some

01:01:30.940 --> 01:01:32.280
[Guest]: random nobleman.

01:01:32.280 --> 01:01:36.860
[Guest]: But because, you know, so these things always happen in battle, these comical, somewhat,

01:01:36.860 --> 01:01:40.320
[Guest]: you know, unglamorous, unheroic situations.

01:01:40.320 --> 01:01:42.600
[Amit Varma]: Really comic, almost lapstick situations.

01:01:42.600 --> 01:01:45.900
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I mean, I'm a proponent of the keto diet, I often say sugar is poison.

01:01:45.900 --> 01:01:47.840
[Amit Varma]: So you could argue that by carrying sugarcane for the...

01:01:47.840 --> 01:01:49.600
[Amit Varma]: You say that as we sip coca-cola here.

01:01:49.600 --> 01:01:50.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, Diet Coke.

01:01:50.600 --> 01:01:52.560
[Amit Varma]: No sugar is written here.

01:01:52.560 --> 01:01:56.240
[Amit Varma]: So you know, so when the raya was carrying sugarcane for the enemy, he was in a sense

01:01:56.240 --> 01:01:59.920
[Amit Varma]: contributing to the eventual downfall.

01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:03.920
[Amit Varma]: What's also interesting here is, you know, people often paint, you know, Vijayanagara

01:02:03.920 --> 01:02:04.920
[Amit Varma]: as a Hindu empire.

01:02:04.920 --> 01:02:09.360
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it might seem that, okay, they're fighting the sultans, the Bahmani empire,

01:02:09.360 --> 01:02:11.680
[Amit Varma]: and therefore it's a Hindu versus Muslim thing.

01:02:11.680 --> 01:02:16.520
[Amit Varma]: And you point out here that Amit Shah, on the one hand, yes, whenever he captured 20,000

01:02:16.520 --> 01:02:20.400
[Amit Varma]: Hindus, he held a feast, for example, which is an interesting factoid.

01:02:20.400 --> 01:02:25.560
[Guest]: And one wonders, it's a doubtful claim, not captured, killed.

01:02:25.560 --> 01:02:29.400
[Guest]: The idea is that every time he killed 20,000 Hindus, he would hold a feast.

01:02:29.400 --> 01:02:33.240
[Guest]: Now it's simply improbable, because, you know, if he was killing 20,000 Hindus on such a

01:02:33.240 --> 01:02:36.760
[Guest]: regular basis, Vijayanagara would have collapsed, because we don't know the exact population

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:37.760
[Guest]: figures.

01:02:37.760 --> 01:02:41.840
[Guest]: But we do know from global population trends, etc, that that sort of slaughter is impossible.

01:02:41.840 --> 01:02:45.560
[Guest]: Because Vijayanagara went on to have a great golden age after this, although, of course,

01:02:45.560 --> 01:02:49.920
[Guest]: golden age is not a concept historians sort of, but the idea is that Vijayanagara grew

01:02:49.920 --> 01:02:50.920
[Guest]: after that.

01:02:50.920 --> 01:02:54.040
[Guest]: It would not have been possible if 20,000 people were being slaughtered on a daily basis.

01:02:54.040 --> 01:02:58.280
[Amit Varma]: But the point you sort of make here is that even though this sort of sentiment was there,

01:02:58.280 --> 01:03:02.480
[Amit Varma]: he was he's actually celebrated in the South by Hindus even today.

01:03:02.480 --> 01:03:03.480
[Guest]: So that's what I'm saying.

01:03:03.480 --> 01:03:07.960
[Guest]: So his own chroniclers will say, oh, yes, he killed 20,000 individuals on a daily basis.

01:03:07.960 --> 01:03:09.160
[Guest]: It's an exaggeration.

01:03:09.160 --> 01:03:13.040
[Guest]: The idea is that, yes, he killed a large number of people in the course of these conquests.

01:03:13.040 --> 01:03:17.320
[Guest]: But in reality, you know, he's he's worshipped by Hindus, the Lingayats come to his tomb

01:03:17.320 --> 01:03:21.880
[Guest]: every year, and they perform on his birth anniversary, a certain ritual where they smash the coconut

01:03:21.880 --> 01:03:23.680
[Guest]: and they do everything in a Hindu way.

01:03:23.680 --> 01:03:26.320
[Guest]: And he was a great patron of Sufis and others.

01:03:26.320 --> 01:03:30.320
[Guest]: And this is the complexity that the Deccan highlights, which is that this binary Hindu

01:03:30.320 --> 01:03:32.440
[Guest]: Muslim divide does not quite work.

01:03:32.440 --> 01:03:37.280
[Guest]: There's Vijayanagara, for example, on the one hand, as I said, they already called themselves

01:03:37.280 --> 01:03:43.200
[Guest]: sultans because they are no Kwams appropriating an Islamic title and using it for themselves.

01:03:43.200 --> 01:03:47.160
[Guest]: They often, you know, there's one sultan later in the Adil Shahi kingdom, which is one of

01:03:47.160 --> 01:03:53.660
[Guest]: the Bahmani successor states, where one sultan dismisses 3000 Persian soldiers and warriors

01:03:53.660 --> 01:03:54.660
[Guest]: he has.

01:03:54.660 --> 01:03:55.660
[Guest]: Where did they go?

01:03:55.660 --> 01:03:58.680
[Guest]: They trot down all the way to the south and seek service in Vijayanagara.

01:03:58.680 --> 01:04:01.920
[Guest]: Vijayanagara had its own Muslims, it had its own mosques at one point.

01:04:01.920 --> 01:04:05.440
[Guest]: The last emperor of Vijayanagara even allowed the eating of beef because he didn't want

01:04:05.440 --> 01:04:06.440
[Guest]: to.

01:04:06.440 --> 01:04:10.240
[Guest]: Similarly, the Quran was always placed in court because the Muslim soldiers said they

01:04:10.240 --> 01:04:14.400
[Guest]: couldn't bow before a Hindu or any other human being as such.

01:04:14.400 --> 01:04:16.640
[Guest]: Therefore, they would bow in front of the Quran instead.

01:04:16.640 --> 01:04:17.640
[Amit Varma]: And the Quran was behind his throne.

01:04:17.640 --> 01:04:20.680
[Guest]: The Quran was kept near the throne so that, you know, they wouldn't be awkward about bowing

01:04:20.680 --> 01:04:21.680
[Guest]: in front of him.

01:04:21.680 --> 01:04:24.600
[Guest]: So the idea was that it was much more complicated.

01:04:24.600 --> 01:04:30.280
[Guest]: It's encapsulated best in the 1565 battle of Talikota, which is where Vijayanagara is

01:04:30.280 --> 01:04:34.520
[Guest]: finally, the city falls and the empire starts disintegrating and the sultans of the Deccan

01:04:34.520 --> 01:04:38.240
[Guest]: take over and start, you know, really win that historic battle.

01:04:38.240 --> 01:04:41.880
[Guest]: What's interesting is most of the, especially right-wing historians and the Twitter school

01:04:41.880 --> 01:04:45.840
[Guest]: of history, which is the screenshot school of history, they say, oh, this is a Hindu

01:04:45.840 --> 01:04:48.960
[Guest]: empire being destroyed by these Muslim sultans.

01:04:48.960 --> 01:04:53.640
[Guest]: Complicated history here, because what happens is the emperor of Vijayanagara, who's leading

01:04:53.640 --> 01:04:58.360
[Guest]: the Vijayanagara forces, he began his career in the court of the Qutub Shah of Golconda.

01:04:58.360 --> 01:05:00.200
[Guest]: He was a nobleman of a Muslim sultan.

01:05:00.200 --> 01:05:04.240
[Guest]: He only ended up becoming emperor of Vijayanagara because he married Krishnadevaraya's daughter.

01:05:04.240 --> 01:05:07.840
[Guest]: The Qutub Shah who was fighting at that battle, he lived seven years as a teenager from the

01:05:07.840 --> 01:05:13.200
[Guest]: age of about 15 or something till, you know, his early 20s in Vijayanagara, where he Teluguized

01:05:13.200 --> 01:05:15.300
[Guest]: his name from Ibrahim to Abhirama.

01:05:15.300 --> 01:05:19.800
[Guest]: He came back to Golconda eventually, patronized poetry on the Mahabharata, acquired a wife

01:05:19.800 --> 01:05:21.880
[Guest]: who was of Vijayanagara origin.

01:05:21.880 --> 01:05:24.200
[Guest]: He spoke and he's a great patron of Telugu.

01:05:24.200 --> 01:05:25.480
[Guest]: Look at the way poets moved.

01:05:25.480 --> 01:05:30.040
[Guest]: A poet like Shetrayya could compose poetry not only in Madurai and Hindu courts, but

01:05:30.040 --> 01:05:34.960
[Guest]: also for the Qutub Shah of Golconda, he composed 1500 Padams, because the Qutub Shah saw themselves

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:36.880
[Guest]: also as custodians of Telugu heritage.

01:05:36.880 --> 01:05:42.320
[Guest]: Similarly, at the 1565 battle, you have 6000 Marathas, but they're fighting for the sultans.

01:05:42.320 --> 01:05:44.960
[Guest]: You have one Muslim warrior called Ainulmul Gilani.

01:05:44.960 --> 01:05:47.080
[Guest]: He's fighting on the side of the Vijayanagara emperor.

01:05:47.080 --> 01:05:50.760
[Guest]: Now the Twitter school, they pulled out screenshots from recent books that say, oh, Ainulmul

01:05:50.760 --> 01:05:54.640
[Guest]: Gilani, you know, defected and went over to the side of the sultans before the battle

01:05:54.640 --> 01:05:55.640
[Guest]: ended.

01:05:55.640 --> 01:05:56.840
[Guest]: There's no evidence of this.

01:05:56.840 --> 01:06:00.040
[Guest]: I don't know where the stories come from, because the only inscriptional evidence of

01:06:00.040 --> 01:06:04.960
[Guest]: Ainulmul Gilani is where he's called in Telugu Ainumuluka, and he's recorded as giving a

01:06:04.960 --> 01:06:07.440
[Guest]: grant of land to 80 Brahmins.

01:06:07.440 --> 01:06:08.720
[Guest]: So it's very mixed up.

01:06:08.720 --> 01:06:12.920
[Guest]: You can't conveniently make any black and white categorizations.

01:06:12.920 --> 01:06:17.000
[Guest]: Even the Sultanates themselves, the Nizam Shahs of Ahmednagar were descended from a

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:21.040
[Guest]: converted Brahmin, and they actually kept links with their Brahmin relatives.

01:06:21.040 --> 01:06:22.920
[Guest]: They made grants of land to their Brahmin relatives.

01:06:22.920 --> 01:06:25.000
[Guest]: They gave estates to their Brahmin relatives.

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:26.360
[Guest]: They married Persian women.

01:06:26.360 --> 01:06:30.720
[Guest]: The Adil Shah of Bijapur, the Adil Shahi dynasty was founded by a man called Yusuf, who got

01:06:30.720 --> 01:06:33.880
[Guest]: on a boat from Persia to build a career in India.

01:06:33.880 --> 01:06:36.720
[Guest]: Somewhere on the way, he decided, I'm going to start claiming I'm a long lost son of the

01:06:36.720 --> 01:06:38.080
[Guest]: Ottoman emperor.

01:06:38.080 --> 01:06:41.760
[Guest]: Comes here, marries a Maratha woman, and that's how the Adil Shahi dynasty is founded.

01:06:41.760 --> 01:06:45.120
[Guest]: So where people say, oh, the Adil Shahs are Muslims, you're completely forgetting the

01:06:45.120 --> 01:06:47.920
[Guest]: mother, the founding lady, who's a Maratha woman.

01:06:47.920 --> 01:06:52.320
[Guest]: And this Maratha woman is very important because two generations down the line, when her legitimate

01:06:52.320 --> 01:06:56.600
[Guest]: grandson proves to be not up to the mark, she has no issues blinding him, putting him

01:06:56.600 --> 01:06:59.800
[Guest]: to the side and having an illegitimate grandson elevated to power.

01:06:59.800 --> 01:07:03.280
[Guest]: So she was not a docile lady sitting wrapped up in some corner.

01:07:03.280 --> 01:07:05.280
[Guest]: She was a political actor herself.

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:09.060
[Guest]: And different Adil Shahs sometimes highlighted different sides of their heritage.

01:07:09.060 --> 01:07:11.000
[Guest]: So the second Adil Shah was very Persianized.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:12.000
[Guest]: He preferred Persian.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:13.180
[Guest]: He spoke only Persian.

01:07:13.180 --> 01:07:15.400
[Guest]: He dressed his troops in Persian uniforms.

01:07:15.400 --> 01:07:18.880
[Guest]: But then you have someone like Ibrahim Adil Shah II, who was a contemporary of Akbar and

01:07:18.880 --> 01:07:24.040
[Guest]: Jahangir, who is exactly the opposite, where the Mughal envoy finds that barely he doesn't

01:07:24.040 --> 01:07:25.040
[Guest]: like speaking Persian.

01:07:25.040 --> 01:07:26.040
[Guest]: He speaks Marathi.

01:07:26.040 --> 01:07:27.120
[Guest]: He prefers Marathi.

01:07:27.120 --> 01:07:31.840
[Guest]: He was Sunni Muslim, but he wore the Rudraksh mala, painted his nails red and called himself

01:07:31.840 --> 01:07:34.560
[Guest]: the son of Guru Ganapati and the pure Saraswati.

01:07:34.560 --> 01:07:39.120
[Guest]: He was so besotted with Saraswati that he went on to rename his capital from Bijapur

01:07:39.120 --> 01:07:40.440
[Guest]: to Vidyapur.

01:07:40.440 --> 01:07:44.840
[Guest]: So again, he's a Sunni Muslim, but he has these other sides to his identity as well.

01:07:44.840 --> 01:07:49.160
[Guest]: Just as Akbar established Fatehpur Sikri for his great debates with various religious experts

01:07:49.160 --> 01:07:54.000
[Guest]: from other religions, Ibrahim Adil Shah II had his Noraspur, where Jesuits and Shaivites

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:56.480
[Guest]: and everybody could come and discuss religion with him.

01:07:56.480 --> 01:08:01.200
[Guest]: When a trader comes to see him, he finds the Adil Shah surrounded by 500 bejeweled women,

01:08:01.200 --> 01:08:04.480
[Guest]: all of them playing the Veena, because he loved Veena music, you know.

01:08:04.480 --> 01:08:06.160
[Guest]: So the man is very colorful.

01:08:06.160 --> 01:08:08.040
[Guest]: He's very interesting like this.

01:08:08.040 --> 01:08:12.520
[Guest]: So you have the option of looking at him as, oh, Ibrahim equal to Sunni Muslim Sultan.

01:08:12.520 --> 01:08:16.560
[Guest]: But wasn't he a little bit more than that, to the extent that when he died on his tomb,

01:08:16.560 --> 01:08:20.400
[Guest]: you have a very clever inscription that says, it's actually a quote from the Quran, which

01:08:20.400 --> 01:08:22.840
[Guest]: says, no, Ibrahim was not a Jew.

01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:24.280
[Guest]: He was not a Christian.

01:08:24.280 --> 01:08:26.480
[Guest]: Certainly he was not an idolater, that is a Hindu.

01:08:26.480 --> 01:08:28.240
[Guest]: He was a devout Muslim.

01:08:28.240 --> 01:08:32.280
[Guest]: It's almost like he's teasing everybody in a sense of saying that none of you can figure

01:08:32.280 --> 01:08:34.800
[Guest]: out who I was, you know, what my religious identity was.

01:08:34.800 --> 01:08:36.560
[Guest]: So I just put it here on the inscription.

01:08:36.560 --> 01:08:41.120
[Guest]: But the funny thing is, although it says Ibrahim there, there also he's playing a little bit

01:08:41.120 --> 01:08:44.840
[Guest]: of a, there's a little bit of wordplay there because it could either refer to him or it

01:08:44.840 --> 01:08:46.480
[Guest]: could refer to Ibrahim from the Quran.

01:08:46.480 --> 01:08:51.040
[Guest]: So you can't really tell what his final loyalties were, whether he was part Hindu, part Muslim

01:08:51.040 --> 01:08:52.040
[Guest]: or both.

01:08:52.040 --> 01:08:53.760
[Amit Varma]: He had no contradiction there.

01:08:53.760 --> 01:08:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And when I was reading your book, you know, two of the fascinating themes that kind of

01:08:57.240 --> 01:09:00.720
[Amit Varma]: stood out for me were globalization and assimilation.

01:09:00.720 --> 01:09:03.760
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, you have this kind of globalization where you have, say, the soft

01:09:03.760 --> 01:09:09.560
[Amit Varma]: power of the Persians being imported and you see an influence of that in clothes, in food,

01:09:09.560 --> 01:09:10.560
[Amit Varma]: in architecture.

01:09:10.560 --> 01:09:14.880
[Amit Varma]: For example, to quote you again, you write about how Amit Shah started a new style of

01:09:14.880 --> 01:09:19.520
[Amit Varma]: architecture, quote, with the elegance of Iran, the sensuality of South India, even

01:09:19.520 --> 01:09:21.320
[Amit Varma]: the occasional influence from Europe.

01:09:21.320 --> 01:09:27.840
[Guest]: Even Vijayanagar, the so-called elephant stables, the domes, domes are not a South Indian architectural

01:09:27.840 --> 01:09:28.840
[Amit Varma]: style.

01:09:28.840 --> 01:09:30.640
[Amit Varma]: They're borrowed very clearly from Islam.

01:09:30.640 --> 01:09:34.760
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, you have influences from across the world, from Europe, from Africa,

01:09:34.760 --> 01:09:37.080
[Amit Varma]: from the Middle East flooding in.

01:09:37.080 --> 01:09:40.880
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, you also have a remarkable assimilation to the extent of, you know, all

01:09:40.880 --> 01:09:45.480
[Amit Varma]: the things you pointed out that you have these rebel sultans knowing all the local languages,

01:09:45.480 --> 01:09:49.680
[Amit Varma]: marrying local women, adapting to local cultures.

01:09:49.680 --> 01:09:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And this is happening back then before there are, you know, regular flights between these

01:09:53.080 --> 01:09:57.000
[Amit Varma]: two places or YouTube, where you can actually immerse yourself more in the culture.

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:01.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's sort of a reminder of how even in our current day, we might be like so sure

01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:06.120
[Amit Varma]: of what our cultural identity is, but actually it's a blend of just about everything.

01:10:06.120 --> 01:10:07.600
[Guest]: It always is a blend.

01:10:07.600 --> 01:10:10.920
[Guest]: Globalization may be a new word that is in fashion now, but the phenomenon has existed

01:10:10.920 --> 01:10:11.920
[Guest]: always.

01:10:11.920 --> 01:10:15.200
[Guest]: It may not have been as fast and instant as it is today, because there was no internet

01:10:15.200 --> 01:10:17.840
[Guest]: and quick communication and travel, but it existed.

01:10:17.840 --> 01:10:20.960
[Guest]: People always communicated with other cultures and peoples.

01:10:20.960 --> 01:10:23.520
[Guest]: They had no issues absorbing from there.

01:10:23.520 --> 01:10:26.840
[Guest]: Look at some of the names around us now, everybody, you know, recently there was this thing about

01:10:26.840 --> 01:10:29.680
[Guest]: Amit Shah's name, Shah, being a Persian thing.

01:10:29.680 --> 01:10:33.880
[Guest]: Now, of course, in Amit Shah's case, it could have been, I mean, there is a theory that

01:10:33.880 --> 01:10:38.280
[Guest]: it's Sahoo that becomes Shah, but even then Shah is a Persian pronunciation.

01:10:38.280 --> 01:10:42.520
[Guest]: So even if Sahoo adopted Shah, there's a Persian influence there, but forget the Shah because

01:10:42.520 --> 01:10:43.520
[Amit Varma]: that's unsettled.

01:10:43.520 --> 01:10:47.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, even the clothes Amit Shah and Narendra Modi wear, the churidar kurta, I mean, that's

01:10:47.200 --> 01:10:48.200
[Guest]: classically Islamic.

01:10:48.200 --> 01:10:52.760
[Guest]: Look at some of the Peshwas who succeeded the actual Maratha rulers and became the real

01:10:52.760 --> 01:10:54.520
[Guest]: force in the Deccan afterwards.

01:10:54.520 --> 01:10:56.960
[Guest]: The Peshwa, the title itself is Persian.

01:10:56.960 --> 01:10:57.960
[Guest]: It means minister.

01:10:57.960 --> 01:10:58.960
[Guest]: It's a Persian title.

01:10:58.960 --> 01:11:01.480
[Guest]: Devendra Fadnavis is the current chief minister of Maharashtra.

01:11:01.480 --> 01:11:02.480
[Guest]: What is Fadnavis?

01:11:02.480 --> 01:11:03.480
[Guest]: It's a Persian title.

01:11:03.480 --> 01:11:04.480
[Guest]: So these things are not gone.

01:11:04.480 --> 01:11:07.480
[Guest]: I'm not talking about a time that's no, that's left no traces.

01:11:07.480 --> 01:11:09.240
[Guest]: The traces are still in front of us.

01:11:09.240 --> 01:11:10.520
[Guest]: These traces still exist.

01:11:10.520 --> 01:11:12.880
[Guest]: Shivaji himself referred to the Hindu path, Patshahi.

01:11:12.880 --> 01:11:13.880
[Guest]: What is a Patshahi?

01:11:13.880 --> 01:11:14.880
[Guest]: It's derived from Batsha.

01:11:14.880 --> 01:11:18.120
[Guest]: It's again an Islamic influence.

01:11:18.120 --> 01:11:22.720
[Guest]: Look at all the clothes that Shivaji and his contemporaries wore, again, inspired by Islamic

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:23.720
[Guest]: fashions.

01:11:23.720 --> 01:11:26.880
[Guest]: Speaking of Shivaji, you know, Shivaji's father was a man called Shahji.

01:11:26.880 --> 01:11:31.720
[Guest]: Now his grandfather, who was a close associate of the Nizam Shah of Ahmednagar, Maloji, Maloji

01:11:31.720 --> 01:11:33.360
[Guest]: couldn't have sons for a long time.

01:11:33.360 --> 01:11:37.160
[Guest]: So Maloji goes to a holy man and the holy man blesses him and his wife and then eventually

01:11:37.160 --> 01:11:38.480
[Guest]: he has two sons.

01:11:38.480 --> 01:11:40.960
[Guest]: Interestingly, the name of the holy man is Shah Sharif.

01:11:40.960 --> 01:11:42.480
[Guest]: He's a Muslim holy man.

01:11:42.480 --> 01:11:44.000
[Guest]: And what does Maloji name his sons?

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:45.000
[Guest]: Shahji and Sharifji.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:47.780
[Guest]: This is Shivaji's father and uncle.

01:11:47.780 --> 01:11:52.760
[Guest]: If you go to Ellora, where Maloji's Samadhi exists, you know, one scholar, the controversial

01:11:52.760 --> 01:11:56.680
[Guest]: James Lane, has made the mistake of saying that this is a tomb where Maloji is buried.

01:11:56.680 --> 01:11:57.680
[Guest]: It's not a tomb.

01:11:57.680 --> 01:11:58.680
[Guest]: It's a Samadhi.

01:11:58.680 --> 01:12:01.800
[Guest]: But the reason James Lane made the mistake is because if you go to the Samadhi, it looks

01:12:01.800 --> 01:12:03.240
[Guest]: like an Islamic monument.

01:12:03.240 --> 01:12:06.560
[Guest]: It looks exactly like the tombs you'll find in Golconda and other places.

01:12:06.560 --> 01:12:10.040
[Guest]: It's got that Islamic structure with some Hindu influences in terms of the ornamental

01:12:10.040 --> 01:12:13.520
[Guest]: activities but the dome, all of that, if you look at it in one glance, it looks like an

01:12:13.520 --> 01:12:14.520
[Guest]: Islamic structure.

01:12:14.520 --> 01:12:16.000
[Guest]: But whose Samadhi is it?

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:17.280
[Guest]: Shivaji's grandfather.

01:12:17.280 --> 01:12:21.160
[Guest]: Shivaji himself commissioned a Sanskrit poem called the Shivabharata, the Nizam Shah in

01:12:21.160 --> 01:12:22.160
[Guest]: one place.

01:12:22.160 --> 01:12:25.760
[Guest]: Here you see the contradiction emerging, which is that on the one hand, Shivaji claims this

01:12:25.760 --> 01:12:30.720
[Guest]: is Vishnu reincarnated to deliver the world from the oppressions of the Turukas, the Muslim

01:12:30.720 --> 01:12:31.720
[Guest]: kings.

01:12:31.720 --> 01:12:35.180
[Guest]: But on the other hand, it also refers to the Nizam Shah of Ahmednagar as a dharmatma.

01:12:35.180 --> 01:12:40.160
[Guest]: It also refers to the famous African warrior general Malik Ambar as brave as the sun.

01:12:40.160 --> 01:12:44.100
[Guest]: At one point, Malik Ambar is compared to the Hindu god Kartikeya.

01:12:44.100 --> 01:12:48.760
[Guest]: So the idea is that even then, there was this black and whiting of history was very complicated.

01:12:48.760 --> 01:12:50.440
[Guest]: You couldn't do it very easily.

01:12:50.440 --> 01:12:52.880
[Guest]: And even Shivaji himself recognized it.

01:12:52.880 --> 01:12:55.780
[Guest]: And the Shivabharata is a fascinating case and example.

01:12:55.780 --> 01:13:00.120
[Guest]: And Malik Ambar is an even more fascinating case because this, we've discussed the Persian

01:13:00.120 --> 01:13:01.120
[Guest]: influence.

01:13:01.120 --> 01:13:02.120
[Guest]: We've discussed the Marathas.

01:13:02.120 --> 01:13:04.360
[Guest]: We've discussed the Hindu blend with all of this.

01:13:04.360 --> 01:13:08.220
[Guest]: But the other element in the Deccan was the Africans, which is that thousands and thousands

01:13:08.220 --> 01:13:11.900
[Guest]: of Africans came as military slaves to the Deccan year after year.

01:13:11.900 --> 01:13:13.720
[Guest]: And this wasn't merely to the Deccan.

01:13:13.720 --> 01:13:17.840
[Guest]: In the 1200s, in Razia Sultan's time, one of the reasons she was assassinated in Delhi

01:13:17.840 --> 01:13:21.920
[Guest]: was because she had an Abyssinian, an Ethiopian African lover.

01:13:21.920 --> 01:13:26.320
[Guest]: In Bengal, there was a brief Habshi dynasty, which is African slaves kicking out the ruling

01:13:26.320 --> 01:13:28.720
[Guest]: dynasty and seizing power for less than a decade.

01:13:28.720 --> 01:13:30.040
[Guest]: But it existed in Bengal.

01:13:30.040 --> 01:13:34.040
[Guest]: In Uttar Pradesh, an African eunuch founded in Jaunpur, a dynasty that lasted for a while,

01:13:34.040 --> 01:13:35.880
[Guest]: I think, in the 14th century.

01:13:35.880 --> 01:13:37.440
[Guest]: So Africans were always in India.

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:41.960
[Guest]: As late as 1724, the Mysore Maharaja had an African guarding one of his forts.

01:13:41.960 --> 01:13:46.440
[Guest]: The Nizam of Hyderabad and 19th century Africans, but the Deccan, it achieves an even more special

01:13:46.440 --> 01:13:50.840
[Guest]: place because at least two Sultans had African wives.

01:13:50.840 --> 01:13:55.400
[Guest]: That is, picture this, in present day Ahmednagar, which is a tier two town in Maharashtra now,

01:13:55.400 --> 01:14:01.120
[Guest]: there were African queens, two of them in the late 16th century and early 17th century.

01:14:01.120 --> 01:14:04.800
[Guest]: One of them was a daughter of Malik Ambar, who began life as a young boy in the Oromo

01:14:04.800 --> 01:14:10.200
[Guest]: tribe in Ethiopia, gets enslaved when he's about 10-12 years old, gets carted off to

01:14:10.200 --> 01:14:15.280
[Guest]: Baghdad, at some point ends up in the Deccan where he's purchased by the Peshwa of Ahmednagar,

01:14:15.280 --> 01:14:20.640
[Guest]: who is the Peshwa also a black man, who has a thousand other black people he's purchased.

01:14:20.640 --> 01:14:24.680
[Guest]: Malik Ambar then rises slowly, ends up having a small little mercenary force.

01:14:24.680 --> 01:14:29.600
[Guest]: And finally, by the end of the 1500s, he becomes the main man standing between the Mughals

01:14:29.600 --> 01:14:31.400
[Guest]: and the conquest of the Deccan.

01:14:31.400 --> 01:14:35.680
[Guest]: So several generations before Shivaji, with Shivaji's grandfather as one of his right

01:14:35.680 --> 01:14:40.720
[Guest]: hand men, it was this African man who had adopted India as his home, become a Muslim,

01:14:40.720 --> 01:14:44.720
[Guest]: who was the main problem for the Mughals in terms of conquering the Deccan.

01:14:44.720 --> 01:14:48.760
[Guest]: Jahangir, if you read the Jahangir Nama, it's quite fascinating, Jahangir is constantly

01:14:48.760 --> 01:14:50.120
[Guest]: bitching and hating on this man.

01:14:50.120 --> 01:14:55.000
[Guest]: He calls him Ambar the ill-starred, Ambar the black-faced, Ambar that disastrous man,

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:57.640
[Guest]: because he can't conquer this man, Ambar is too clever.

01:14:57.640 --> 01:15:00.960
[Guest]: And Ambar is the one who develops what is called Bargigiri, guerrilla warfare, which

01:15:00.960 --> 01:15:04.160
[Guest]: is what Shivaji then takes to perfection a few generations later.

01:15:04.160 --> 01:15:08.480
[Guest]: And Shivaji therefore, as I said, describes Ambar as brave as the sun in his own Shiva

01:15:08.480 --> 01:15:12.160
[Guest]: Bharata, because Ambar was a legend, he was a remarkable man.

01:15:12.160 --> 01:15:16.040
[Guest]: Jahangir was so frustrated with Ambar and his inability to conquer and reduce Ambar

01:15:16.040 --> 01:15:19.640
[Guest]: to nothing, that he commissioned a painting which shows Jahangir shooting an arrow at

01:15:19.640 --> 01:15:22.480
[Guest]: Ambar's severed head, impaled on a spear.

01:15:22.480 --> 01:15:24.960
[Guest]: It was something Jahangir never managed to do in real life.

01:15:24.960 --> 01:15:28.080
[Guest]: But he fantasized in art what he couldn't achieve in real life.

01:15:28.080 --> 01:15:31.920
[Guest]: And Ambar, as it happened, died a very old man in his 80s, comfortable and secure in

01:15:31.920 --> 01:15:34.960
[Guest]: his fortress, undefeated by the Mughals.

01:15:34.960 --> 01:15:39.620
[Guest]: So the Deccan was a place where not only Persians, Marathas, Vijayanagar existed, but also thousands

01:15:39.620 --> 01:15:40.960
[Guest]: of Africans who came in.

01:15:40.960 --> 01:15:43.680
[Guest]: All of them left their marks on this place.

01:15:43.680 --> 01:15:47.200
[Guest]: And many of these people married Maratha women, and many of their descendants would have been

01:15:47.200 --> 01:15:48.760
[Guest]: absorbed into the community.

01:15:48.760 --> 01:15:53.240
[Guest]: So it's a mix of all these, not only cultural influences, but also blood from so many places.

01:15:53.240 --> 01:15:57.400
[Amit Varma]: And many of us are probably descended from Africans in a more immediate sense than we

01:15:57.400 --> 01:15:58.400
[Amit Varma]: think.

01:15:58.400 --> 01:15:59.400
[Amit Varma]: Yes, I think so.

01:15:59.400 --> 01:16:00.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:16:00.400 --> 01:16:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And just tangential question that occurs to me, how would Shivaji have known about Malik

01:16:02.880 --> 01:16:03.880
[Amit Varma]: Ambar?

01:16:03.880 --> 01:16:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Because you don't have history books, you don't have podcasts, you don't have YouTube.

01:16:06.320 --> 01:16:10.000
[Guest]: I mean, family tradition, as I said, Shivaji's father knew Ambar, Shivaji's grandfather was

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:11.000
[Amit Varma]: a priest.

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:12.000
[Guest]: So it's all oral traditions.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:13.000
[Guest]: It's only two generations.

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:14.000
[Guest]: Right.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:17.680
[Guest]: When your grandfather is closely associated with him, and you commission this.

01:16:17.680 --> 01:16:20.360
[Guest]: So Ambar dies in the late 1620s.

01:16:20.360 --> 01:16:24.720
[Guest]: And in the 1680s, Shivaji, several decades later, Shivaji commissions the Shivabharata.

01:16:24.720 --> 01:16:26.520
[Guest]: Why is Ambar compared to Kartikeya?

01:16:26.520 --> 01:16:29.940
[Guest]: Because Ambar's memory and his legacy is still standing tall.

01:16:29.940 --> 01:16:34.200
[Guest]: That's something that clearly inspired Shivaji, for Shivaji to give Ambar such prominence

01:16:34.200 --> 01:16:38.240
[Guest]: in the Shivabharata, which is otherwise a work of eulogy for Shivaji himself.

01:16:38.240 --> 01:16:41.960
[Guest]: It's a Sanskrit poem that talks about Shivaji's conquests and adventures.

01:16:41.960 --> 01:16:44.120
[Amit Varma]: But Ambar is a very prominent figure there.

01:16:44.120 --> 01:16:49.720
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of head back now to the Bahmanis again and trace, go all the way to how they

01:16:49.720 --> 01:16:50.720
[Amit Varma]: fell.

01:16:50.720 --> 01:16:54.960
[Amit Varma]: You talk about like, another bit that fascinated me was the grandsons of Amritsar, Humayun

01:16:54.960 --> 01:16:57.840
[Amit Varma]: the cruel and Hassan.

01:16:57.840 --> 01:17:02.760
[Amit Varma]: And you write about how Hassan was made the Sultan, and then the paying crowds gathered

01:17:02.760 --> 01:17:06.760
[Amit Varma]: outside Humayun's palace waiting to sort of plunder it.

01:17:06.760 --> 01:17:10.280
[Amit Varma]: And then he managed to get out of that and he took power from Hassan and then, quote,

01:17:10.280 --> 01:17:12.800
[Guest]: And he did it very cleverly, he didn't have men with him.

01:17:12.800 --> 01:17:13.800
[Guest]: So what did he do?

01:17:13.800 --> 01:17:17.520
[Guest]: He got a holy man to come and stand next to him, because that's a different kind of legitimacy.

01:17:17.520 --> 01:17:20.360
[Guest]: And then this crowd sort of backed off when they saw the holy man.

01:17:20.360 --> 01:17:25.320
[Guest]: And then he walks all the way to Hassan, who's sitting in the darbar on the throne, walks

01:17:25.320 --> 01:17:29.440
[Guest]: up to him, slaps him, pushes him off the throne and takes a seat on the throne.

01:17:29.440 --> 01:17:32.360
[Guest]: This is so hilarious to just picture the scene.

01:17:32.360 --> 01:17:38.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and then a little Hassan and then you say, quote, Humayun had, quote, Hassan thrown

01:17:38.360 --> 01:17:43.040
[Amit Varma]: before tigers, ordered some of his adherents to be cast into cauldrons full of boiling

01:17:43.040 --> 01:17:48.600
[Amit Varma]: water and oil and release mad elephants and other wild bees to prey upon the unfortunate

01:17:48.600 --> 01:17:49.600
[Guest]: victims.

01:17:49.600 --> 01:17:50.600
[Guest]: Stop, quote.

01:17:50.600 --> 01:17:55.960
[Guest]: Yeah, again, as I said, violence displayed and violence used in a very visually ghastly

01:17:55.960 --> 01:18:00.080
[Guest]: fashion just to sort of reinforce the idea that don't mess with me.

01:18:00.080 --> 01:18:01.080
[Amit Varma]: And why mad elephants?

01:18:01.080 --> 01:18:04.240
[Guest]: You mentioned mad elephants, like multiple times, they appear in the sources.

01:18:04.240 --> 01:18:08.240
[Guest]: I think mad in the sense that, you know, very aggressive sort of elephants, which will come

01:18:08.240 --> 01:18:10.240
[Guest]: and sort of destroy you no matter what.

01:18:10.240 --> 01:18:13.440
[Guest]: Otherwise, elephants, if it's a regular elephant that's standing there, why would it come and

01:18:13.440 --> 01:18:14.440
[Guest]: trample you?

01:18:14.440 --> 01:18:18.640
[Guest]: You know, so if it has to be done with as much brutality as possible, you need an elephant

01:18:18.640 --> 01:18:21.240
[Guest]: that's really got something going for it.

01:18:21.240 --> 01:18:27.640
[Amit Varma]: Pissed off, unfed, made to, and then you talk about how Humayun the cruel was stabbed by

01:18:27.640 --> 01:18:32.040
[Amit Varma]: a maidservant, which is also an ignominious way to die, I suppose, for a guy like that.

01:18:32.040 --> 01:18:33.880
[Guest]: How did the Bamani Empire come to an end?

01:18:33.880 --> 01:18:37.320
[Guest]: The Bamani Empire came to an end because of the weight of its own internal contradictions.

01:18:37.320 --> 01:18:43.600
[Guest]: As I said, at the height of its confidence, absorbing, say, you know, a lot of Persians,

01:18:43.600 --> 01:18:47.720
[Guest]: absorbing the local Maratha element, absorbing culture from Vijayanagara, all that is possible.

01:18:47.720 --> 01:18:51.640
[Amit Varma]: And also the Dakhnis, like you pointed out, are basically, they've come from the Turks

01:18:51.640 --> 01:18:52.640
[Guest]: and they're Sunni Muslims.

01:18:52.640 --> 01:18:54.960
[Guest]: They're either people who come from the north, but they're essentially Indian in the sense

01:18:54.960 --> 01:18:58.840
[Guest]: that largely the Dakhnis are Sunni Muslims, they're people who've converted within India

01:18:58.840 --> 01:19:03.280
[Guest]: and they're considered Hindustani Muslims, whereas the Westerners or the Afakhis, they

01:19:03.280 --> 01:19:06.960
[Guest]: are Shias, largely, who've come in from Persia later.

01:19:06.960 --> 01:19:10.240
[Guest]: And the thing is, the Westerners have a little bit of a superiority complex in the Bamani

01:19:10.240 --> 01:19:14.520
[Guest]: court, because as I said, there's this Persian, Persian is considered the latest soft power

01:19:14.520 --> 01:19:15.520
[Guest]: asset.

01:19:15.520 --> 01:19:20.900
[Guest]: It's very glamorous, etc. compared to which the Dakhnis look a little bit like poor cousins.

01:19:20.900 --> 01:19:23.120
[Guest]: So there's that internal sort of rivalry there.

01:19:23.120 --> 01:19:25.200
[Amit Varma]: And would it be correct to say that the language also plays a part?

01:19:25.200 --> 01:19:28.160
[Guest]: So the Persian at that time is like the English of today, the elite speaker.

01:19:28.160 --> 01:19:32.200
[Guest]: In fact, Persian was a Persian was diplomatic language till the early 19th century.

01:19:32.200 --> 01:19:35.840
[Guest]: And I was stunned when I was working on my first book, letters written by the Maharani

01:19:35.840 --> 01:19:39.560
[Guest]: of Travancore in the 1810s to the British governor, they're in Persian.

01:19:39.560 --> 01:19:43.240
[Guest]: It wasn't even in English, it was in Persian, because even the British recognized Persian

01:19:43.240 --> 01:19:45.760
[Guest]: as the international language in this part of the world.

01:19:45.760 --> 01:19:48.500
[Guest]: And Persian had therefore great value attached to it.

01:19:48.500 --> 01:19:50.900
[Guest]: So therefore, the Persian faction was very influential.

01:19:50.900 --> 01:19:53.680
[Guest]: So you have the Persian faction, you have the Dakhni faction, you have the Marathas,

01:19:53.680 --> 01:19:57.080
[Guest]: you have the Africans, all of these are groups.

01:19:57.080 --> 01:20:02.040
[Guest]: So in the end, the contradiction was that if it was a sultan who was confident and broadminded

01:20:02.040 --> 01:20:06.000
[Guest]: enough, he was able to take all these people along with him, he could inspire that confidence.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:09.380
[Guest]: But some sultans made the mistake of playing these groups against each other.

01:20:09.380 --> 01:20:13.320
[Guest]: So as political power started weakening a little bit, they started being tempted to

01:20:13.320 --> 01:20:16.000
[Guest]: play one group against the other for their own benefit.

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:21.480
[Guest]: So this led to violence between these groups, and slowly the differences started solidifying.

01:20:21.480 --> 01:20:25.360
[Guest]: And you know, as I said, this was a military state, and these borders and loyalties are

01:20:25.360 --> 01:20:26.360
[Guest]: not constant.

01:20:26.360 --> 01:20:30.680
[Guest]: You can easily, you know, one entire group can remove themselves from this court and

01:20:30.680 --> 01:20:32.540
[Guest]: find patronage in the next court.

01:20:32.540 --> 01:20:36.120
[Guest]: So in that sense, and different sultans, so within the Bahmani state, by the end of their

01:20:36.120 --> 01:20:40.040
[Guest]: days of glory, as it were, what you have is a weak sultan who doesn't, who can't hold

01:20:40.040 --> 01:20:42.960
[Guest]: all these factions together, and powerful governors.

01:20:42.960 --> 01:20:47.080
[Guest]: So the Nizam Shah is converted from a Dakhni, which is a converted Brahmin, and they're

01:20:47.080 --> 01:20:50.520
[Guest]: the first ones to establish an independent kingdom and found the city of Ahmednagar and

01:20:50.520 --> 01:20:51.520
[Guest]: so on.

01:20:51.520 --> 01:20:52.520
[Guest]: And they become an independent kingdom.

01:20:52.520 --> 01:20:55.760
[Guest]: Technically, the Bahmani sultan is maintained for another 40-45 years.

01:20:55.760 --> 01:21:00.700
[Guest]: But slowly the power, they're just a cipher, the final Bahmani sultans are reduced to picking

01:21:00.700 --> 01:21:03.760
[Guest]: out the jewels from their crown and selling it, and then picking out things from their

01:21:03.760 --> 01:21:06.340
[Guest]: throne and selling it because they have no money.

01:21:06.340 --> 01:21:09.640
[Guest]: Then you have the Adil Shah who realizes, hold on, the kingdom is falling to bits, let

01:21:09.640 --> 01:21:12.040
[Guest]: me also sort of consolidate my little corner somewhere.

01:21:12.040 --> 01:21:13.040
[Amit Varma]: That's Bijapur, basically.

01:21:13.040 --> 01:21:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Bijapur.

01:21:14.040 --> 01:21:16.200
[Guest]: The Qutub Shah of Golconda does the same in Golconda.

01:21:16.200 --> 01:21:20.720
[Guest]: Although he never proclaims independence, he still carves out his own independent realm.

01:21:20.720 --> 01:21:23.980
[Guest]: And you know, he sends a tribute annually to the sultan, but then when that particular

01:21:23.980 --> 01:21:25.560
[Guest]: sultan dies, he stops.

01:21:25.560 --> 01:21:27.280
[Guest]: So eventually the sultans are left with nothing.

01:21:27.280 --> 01:21:30.960
[Guest]: And the last, it's quite tragic, the last descendant of the Bahmani sultans at the end

01:21:30.960 --> 01:21:36.440
[Guest]: of the 1530s is reduced to getting on a ship and going off to Mecca because he has nothing

01:21:36.440 --> 01:21:37.440
[Guest]: left here.

01:21:37.440 --> 01:21:38.440
[Guest]: He's nobody.

01:21:38.440 --> 01:21:41.160
[Guest]: So the Bahmani sultanate essentially disintegrates.

01:21:41.160 --> 01:21:42.640
[Guest]: Why do I call them rebel sultans?

01:21:42.640 --> 01:21:47.720
[Guest]: Because the Bahmani sultanate was established by a set of people in rebellion from Delhi

01:21:47.720 --> 01:21:52.360
[Guest]: and it was destabilized by another set of rebels who sort of rebelled against the Bahmani

01:21:52.360 --> 01:21:56.440
[Guest]: sultan, founded their own kingdoms and they were the next generation of rebel sultans

01:21:56.440 --> 01:21:57.440
[Guest]: as it were.

01:21:57.440 --> 01:21:59.840
[Guest]: So for about 150 years, the Bahmanis are in charge.

01:21:59.840 --> 01:22:05.120
[Guest]: Then you have a second cycle which ends in the late 17th century when successive states

01:22:05.120 --> 01:22:10.680
[Guest]: come into the picture and the Bahmani sultanate disintegrates into five smaller kingdoms.

01:22:10.680 --> 01:22:12.560
[Amit Varma]: But each of them very powerful and strong.

01:22:12.560 --> 01:22:16.640
[Amit Varma]: And it's also interesting how sort of that dynasty, the Bahmani dynasty sort of whimpers

01:22:16.640 --> 01:22:19.320
[Amit Varma]: out like the Mughals do almost.

01:22:19.320 --> 01:22:22.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's not like someone beheaded and you become a non-entity.

01:22:22.280 --> 01:22:25.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you just become absolutely nobody.

01:22:25.360 --> 01:22:30.960
[Amit Varma]: Let's, you know, now before we talk about those sort of rebel sultans who succeed the

01:22:30.960 --> 01:22:33.360
[Amit Varma]: Bahmani empire, let's talk a bit about Vijayanagara.

01:22:33.360 --> 01:22:34.360
[Amit Varma]: Bring me up to speed.

01:22:34.360 --> 01:22:38.840
[Guest]: Vijayanagara is going through its own internal issues, which is that unlike the Bahmani state

01:22:38.840 --> 01:22:42.680
[Guest]: which was disintegrated into several pieces, Vijayanagara, you have three dynasties that

01:22:42.680 --> 01:22:43.680
[Guest]: come and fall.

01:22:43.680 --> 01:22:47.320
[Guest]: So first you have the original dynasty, the Sangama brothers who found Vijayanagara.

01:22:47.320 --> 01:22:49.200
[Guest]: They rule for a certain time.

01:22:49.200 --> 01:22:52.720
[Guest]: Then you have a short-lived dynasty in the middle, which is a military general who takes

01:22:52.720 --> 01:22:56.120
[Guest]: over and then his son, he dies, his son is sort of kicked out.

01:22:56.120 --> 01:23:00.160
[Guest]: And then finally, Krishnadevaraya's dynasty comes to power.

01:23:00.160 --> 01:23:05.000
[Guest]: And if the initial ones founded the kingdom, and I think they were largely Shaivites, Krishnadevaraya's

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:08.040
[Guest]: time is you start seeing more of a Vaishnava influence.

01:23:08.040 --> 01:23:11.920
[Guest]: And Vijayanagara at this time, again, as I said, is absorbing all these influences.

01:23:11.920 --> 01:23:15.640
[Guest]: It's expanding its boundaries in the south, failing frustratingly when it comes to the

01:23:15.640 --> 01:23:19.400
[Guest]: sultans because the sultans have more technology as far as Vijayanagara is concerned.

01:23:19.400 --> 01:23:23.440
[Guest]: And at certain times, the Vijayanagara kings have to pay tribute to the sultans.

01:23:23.440 --> 01:23:27.280
[Guest]: Sometimes the sultans have to come and enforce it, but they have to end up paying tribute.

01:23:27.280 --> 01:23:31.320
[Guest]: Interestingly, after the splinter states come to power in the northern deck and the Adil

01:23:31.320 --> 01:23:36.680
[Guest]: Shahs of Bijapur, the Qutub Shahs in Golconda and the Nizam Shahs in Ahmednagar, Vijayanagara

01:23:36.680 --> 01:23:39.600
[Guest]: then has greater influence because Vijayanagara is still solid.

01:23:39.600 --> 01:23:41.920
[Guest]: It's still one big empire.

01:23:41.920 --> 01:23:45.360
[Guest]: And then the last, the mistake was that the last emperor of Vijayanagara, and when I say

01:23:45.360 --> 01:23:49.120
[Guest]: last, Vijayanagara survived, but the last main character before the historic battle

01:23:49.120 --> 01:23:54.040
[Guest]: of Talikota in 1565, he starts meddling a little too much in these northern kingdoms.

01:23:54.040 --> 01:23:56.480
[Guest]: Now, again, there's no Hindu-Muslim divide here.

01:23:56.480 --> 01:24:00.480
[Guest]: So one of the Adil Shahs of Bijapur was adopted by this last emperor of Vijayanagara as his

01:24:00.480 --> 01:24:01.560
[Guest]: own son.

01:24:01.560 --> 01:24:05.680
[Guest]: As I said, the Qutub Shah, when he had no place in his brother's court, he came and

01:24:05.680 --> 01:24:06.680
[Guest]: lived in exile in Vijayanagara.

01:24:06.680 --> 01:24:11.080
[Guest]: There are lots of continuities and commonalities between them, but Vijayanagara starts getting

01:24:11.080 --> 01:24:14.720
[Guest]: tempted a little too much to start playing politics with these people.

01:24:14.720 --> 01:24:18.520
[Guest]: And these northern kings realized that, hold on, we're all losing and Vijayanagara is slowly

01:24:18.520 --> 01:24:20.280
[Guest]: gaining at our expense.

01:24:20.280 --> 01:24:24.860
[Guest]: So finally, for the one time in history where their survival was threatened, they come together.

01:24:24.860 --> 01:24:28.120
[Guest]: And of course, this is justified in the name of Islam and all of that, but that's not the

01:24:28.120 --> 01:24:29.120
[Guest]: point.

01:24:29.120 --> 01:24:30.120
[Guest]: The point is politics.

01:24:30.120 --> 01:24:31.840
[Guest]: They come together, they decide this is a common enemy.

01:24:31.840 --> 01:24:35.440
[Guest]: We may all hate each other, but for the time being, this is our biggest threat.

01:24:35.440 --> 01:24:40.600
[Guest]: So, they come to a series of marital alliances where, say, one of the Nizam Shahi princesses,

01:24:40.600 --> 01:24:43.400
[Guest]: the famous Chand Bibi, is given in marriage to the Adil Shah.

01:24:43.400 --> 01:24:45.840
[Guest]: Another daughter of the Nizam Shah goes off to the Qutub Shah family.

01:24:45.840 --> 01:24:49.600
[Guest]: Similarly, girls are exchanged from those families and they have a new alliance.

01:24:49.600 --> 01:24:54.120
[Guest]: And that's when Vijayanagara is finally destroyed in that historic battle in Talikota and the

01:24:54.120 --> 01:24:56.240
[Guest]: city is sacked and taken.

01:24:56.240 --> 01:24:59.800
[Guest]: Interestingly, the Sultans don't go out and try and conquer all of Vijayanagara.

01:24:59.800 --> 01:25:02.200
[Guest]: Once the city is destroyed, they go back to their capitals.

01:25:02.200 --> 01:25:06.920
[Guest]: They gain some territory, but they're not trying to completely, you know, wipe out Vijayanagara

01:25:06.920 --> 01:25:07.920
[Guest]: from the map of India.

01:25:07.920 --> 01:25:08.920
[Guest]: That's not happening.

01:25:08.920 --> 01:25:11.600
[Guest]: Vijayanagara is still seen as a legitimate entity.

01:25:11.600 --> 01:25:17.360
[Guest]: And you see some of this in the texts as well, where there's this later text called the Rayavachakamu,

01:25:17.360 --> 01:25:23.000
[Guest]: where also you find some Hindu-Muslim polemics, the early beginnings of a certain polemical

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:27.480
[Guest]: line that starts occurring at this time, where it's written after Krishnadevaraya's time,

01:25:27.480 --> 01:25:32.240
[Guest]: 70-80 years later, but it talks about how, it says how all the Sultans of the Deccan

01:25:32.240 --> 01:25:36.360
[Guest]: are evil, men are being cut into half in the streets, they're all greedy, their own ministers

01:25:36.360 --> 01:25:37.360
[Guest]: are scared of them.

01:25:37.360 --> 01:25:40.560
[Guest]: Basically, it's compared to the land of death, the Yama's kingdom.

01:25:40.560 --> 01:25:42.960
[Guest]: That's how bad the Deccan Sultans are.

01:25:42.960 --> 01:25:46.360
[Guest]: Some people interpret this thing, say all these Muslims are so bad and the Hindus are

01:25:46.360 --> 01:25:47.920
[Guest]: clearly saying this is bad.

01:25:47.920 --> 01:25:50.960
[Guest]: But the same Rayavachakamu also says the Mughal Emperor is great.

01:25:50.960 --> 01:25:53.720
[Guest]: It says the Mughal Emperor is blessed by Kashi Vishwanath.

01:25:53.720 --> 01:25:58.480
[Guest]: So just as Vijayanagara is blessed by Tirupati, the Gajapati of Orissa is blessed by Jagannath

01:25:58.480 --> 01:26:01.320
[Guest]: of Puri, the Mughals are blessed by Kashi Vishwanath.

01:26:01.320 --> 01:26:05.960
[Guest]: So they recognized to make the Deccan Sultans look bad, they play up the Mughals and make

01:26:05.960 --> 01:26:06.960
[Guest]: the Mughals look good.

01:26:06.960 --> 01:26:10.160
[Guest]: So again, Vijayanagara wasn't playing a Hindu-Muslim game.

01:26:10.160 --> 01:26:14.120
[Guest]: If they were, Bukka, one of the founders of Vijayanagara, who claimed in his inscriptions

01:26:14.120 --> 01:26:18.720
[Guest]: to be Krishna reborn to destroy the Mlecchas, which is the Muslims, he had no issues trying

01:26:18.720 --> 01:26:22.120
[Guest]: to seek an alliance with Feroz Shah Bahmani, saying, okay, you and I'll join hands together

01:26:22.120 --> 01:26:25.200
[Guest]: and I'll come from the south, you come from the north and we'll destroy the Bahmani Sultanate

01:26:25.200 --> 01:26:26.320
[Guest]: in the center.

01:26:26.320 --> 01:26:28.640
[Guest]: So again, politics is what guides it.

01:26:28.640 --> 01:26:30.280
[Guest]: But Vijayanagara, of course, has its own issues.

01:26:30.280 --> 01:26:33.040
[Guest]: You have these coups that are happening in Vijayanagara and so on.

01:26:33.040 --> 01:26:37.680
[Guest]: But finally, of course, it was overstretched, where the last emperor of Vijayanagara played,

01:26:37.680 --> 01:26:41.860
[Guest]: he tried to gamble in a way that didn't quite work out in the way he thought.

01:26:41.860 --> 01:26:46.440
[Guest]: And the Sultanate, instead of breaking away and his divine rule succeeding, they instead

01:26:46.440 --> 01:26:49.280
[Guest]: united and they decided to teach Vijayanagara a lesson.

01:26:49.280 --> 01:26:52.520
[Amit Varma]: And I think this was partly because, like you point out in the book, he got incredibly

01:26:52.520 --> 01:26:57.600
[Amit Varma]: arrogant, he humiliated the Nizam Shah more than he should have in a particular instance.

01:26:57.600 --> 01:27:01.480
[Amit Varma]: And then despite allying with the others to fight with the Nizam Shah, he annexed part

01:27:01.480 --> 01:27:06.240
[Amit Varma]: of the kingdoms and destroyed mosques, destroyed mosques and all annexations would be accompanied

01:27:06.240 --> 01:27:12.040
[Amit Varma]: by the destruction of mosques and the humiliation of women and there's an interesting legend,

01:27:12.040 --> 01:27:16.120
[Guest]: which is actually a footnote in the book, which is Chand Bibi's mother, Khunza Humayun,

01:27:16.120 --> 01:27:19.680
[Guest]: which is Hussain Nizam Shah, the one who's at this battle, his wife.

01:27:19.680 --> 01:27:24.880
[Guest]: The story goes that, this is from one particular poem from the Ahmednagar court, where Ramaraya,

01:27:24.880 --> 01:27:28.000
[Guest]: the emperor of Vijayanagara demands tribute from Ahmednagar.

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:32.480
[Guest]: And in the list of things that the Nizam Shah should pay, there is a sexually loaded reference

01:27:32.480 --> 01:27:36.800
[Guest]: to Khunza Humayun, the Begum's anklets, saying that, you know, the tribute includes the Begum's

01:27:36.800 --> 01:27:40.240
[Guest]: anklets and Hussain Nizam Shah says, no, I will avenge her honor or whatever.

01:27:40.240 --> 01:27:42.800
[Guest]: Again, it's an excuse to justify what was geopolitics.

01:27:42.800 --> 01:27:45.860
[Guest]: They essentially wanted to destroy each other anyway.

01:27:45.860 --> 01:27:49.080
[Guest]: But it's interesting that a woman appears here at this particular time.

01:27:49.080 --> 01:27:53.200
[Guest]: And as it happens, Khunza Humayun is one of those few women that appears in the history

01:27:53.200 --> 01:27:55.120
[Guest]: of the Deccan as a political figure.

01:27:55.120 --> 01:27:59.520
[Guest]: And of course, she rules for six years after her husband dies, but then her son and his

01:27:59.520 --> 01:28:03.880
[Guest]: coterie eventually topple her and imprison her and sort of wipe her out to the extent

01:28:03.880 --> 01:28:07.920
[Guest]: that she's not only wiped out of records, she's painted over in paintings, she's reduced

01:28:07.920 --> 01:28:12.320
[Guest]: to this giant blot in paintings where her husband still remains intact, but she's been

01:28:12.320 --> 01:28:16.000
[Guest]: reduced to a smudge in these miniature paintings.

01:28:16.000 --> 01:28:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Which brings me down to a question I plan to ask at the end of this, but before we get

01:28:18.800 --> 01:28:23.000
[Amit Varma]: back to the narrative, just to take it up, and you'd mentioned this yourself before is

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:27.560
[Amit Varma]: how women are viewed in history and how their roles are recorded in history.

01:28:27.560 --> 01:28:30.840
[Guest]: It's complicated because, you know, the further back you go in time, you find that most of

01:28:30.840 --> 01:28:33.960
[Guest]: the material is authored by men, which means there's that male gaze.

01:28:33.960 --> 01:28:36.680
[Guest]: It's largely about men and their battles.

01:28:36.680 --> 01:28:40.560
[Guest]: There are women here and there occasionally, but the voices that tell their story are still

01:28:40.560 --> 01:28:41.560
[Guest]: not female voices.

01:28:41.560 --> 01:28:45.560
[Guest]: They are men who often have their own prejudices, their own biases.

01:28:45.560 --> 01:28:48.640
[Guest]: They often don't approve of these autonomous, strong women.

01:28:48.640 --> 01:28:52.400
[Guest]: So Kunza Humayun, as I was mentioning, she ended up rotting in jail for some 15, 16 years

01:28:52.400 --> 01:28:53.520
[Guest]: before she died.

01:28:53.520 --> 01:28:54.520
[Guest]: She was wiped out.

01:28:54.520 --> 01:28:55.520
[Guest]: She was, there was no glory for her.

01:28:55.520 --> 01:29:00.360
[Guest]: Her daughter, Chand Bibi survives a little bit in legend and popular imagination, partly

01:29:00.360 --> 01:29:04.780
[Guest]: because Chand Bibi died in the course of the Mughal invasion and she died, she was assassinated.

01:29:04.780 --> 01:29:08.040
[Guest]: So that tragedy therefore allowed her to be enshrined as a sort of martyr.

01:29:08.040 --> 01:29:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Before that, she also kind of fought a famous battle, almost taking a man's role and going

01:29:11.840 --> 01:29:12.840
[Guest]: out into the ramparts.

01:29:12.840 --> 01:29:13.840
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:29:13.840 --> 01:29:17.360
[Guest]: When the Mughals breached the fort, she actually went into the breach and ensured it was reconstructed

01:29:17.360 --> 01:29:18.360
[Guest]: and so on.

01:29:18.360 --> 01:29:19.920
[Guest]: So she was a very formidable figure.

01:29:19.920 --> 01:29:24.160
[Guest]: The Mughals themselves were in awe of her, but because she died a martyr, as it were,

01:29:24.160 --> 01:29:26.600
[Guest]: died in the course of battle and not on the battlefield.

01:29:26.600 --> 01:29:27.600
[Guest]: Her own men killed her.

01:29:27.600 --> 01:29:28.600
[Guest]: It was an internal job.

01:29:28.600 --> 01:29:29.600
[Guest]: But she died violently.

01:29:29.600 --> 01:29:34.520
[Guest]: There was a certain romance attached to her and romance therefore keeps the story alive.

01:29:34.520 --> 01:29:38.800
[Guest]: But a more everyday woman like Khunza Humayun, her mother, who didn't die on the edge of

01:29:38.800 --> 01:29:41.680
[Guest]: a sword in a battle, she didn't die violently.

01:29:41.680 --> 01:29:44.140
[Guest]: She tried on an everyday basis to take power.

01:29:44.140 --> 01:29:48.040
[Guest]: She tried on an everyday basis to hold power and the men resented that to the extent that

01:29:48.040 --> 01:29:49.160
[Guest]: they wiped her out.

01:29:49.160 --> 01:29:53.240
[Guest]: So what happens in history is if you're a woman and you play some sort of romantic,

01:29:53.240 --> 01:29:57.560
[Guest]: poetic role, either as a tragic heroine or some sort of sacrificing mother or whatever,

01:29:57.560 --> 01:29:58.760
[Guest]: then you have a place.

01:29:58.760 --> 01:30:00.420
[Guest]: Then your story survives in some ways.

01:30:00.420 --> 01:30:02.160
[Guest]: If you are of interest to the male imagination.

01:30:02.160 --> 01:30:03.560
[Guest]: If you're of interest to the male imagination.

01:30:03.560 --> 01:30:08.080
[Guest]: But if you're a Khunza Humayun who tries to take charge of those bastions of male power

01:30:08.080 --> 01:30:12.240
[Guest]: and use that and exercise that on an everyday basis, then my God, you're going to be wiped

01:30:12.240 --> 01:30:15.200
[Guest]: out of records, wiped out of paintings, wiped out of everything.

01:30:15.200 --> 01:30:17.240
[Amit Varma]: So as a male historian, how do you overcome this?

01:30:17.240 --> 01:30:20.560
[Amit Varma]: Because on one hand, there is a problem that all your sources are written from this male

01:30:20.560 --> 01:30:21.560
[Guest]: gaze.

01:30:21.560 --> 01:30:22.560
[Guest]: What can you do differently?

01:30:22.560 --> 01:30:25.960
[Guest]: So in my first book, I was lucky in that sense, because it taught me a lot, which is that

01:30:25.960 --> 01:30:30.360
[Guest]: my protagonist, my antagonist, they're all women, often the primary material, the letters,

01:30:30.360 --> 01:30:31.360
[Guest]: these are all their letters.

01:30:31.360 --> 01:30:34.040
[Guest]: It's women writing, it's their perspective and so on.

01:30:34.040 --> 01:30:37.120
[Guest]: But with this, with the second book, Rebel Sultans, because as I said, we're going further

01:30:37.120 --> 01:30:39.880
[Guest]: back in time, the material becomes a problem.

01:30:39.880 --> 01:30:41.880
[Guest]: You can consciously try and resurrect these women.

01:30:41.880 --> 01:30:44.520
[Guest]: You can consciously try and tell their stories.

01:30:44.520 --> 01:30:48.020
[Guest]: But if the material doesn't exist, you can't invent stuff.

01:30:48.020 --> 01:30:50.460
[Guest]: So that is the tragedy in history.

01:30:50.460 --> 01:30:55.160
[Guest]: So what I see as the solution is largely more women writing history.

01:30:55.160 --> 01:30:59.500
[Guest]: Because although historians are in the task of connecting the dots, as a man or because

01:30:59.500 --> 01:31:05.360
[Guest]: most textbooks are written by men, we are taught or trained at some ingrained level

01:31:05.360 --> 01:31:09.320
[Guest]: to connect the dots in a certain way, whereas a woman writes history, if more women come

01:31:09.320 --> 01:31:13.320
[Guest]: into history, look at the same material, they will bring a different gaze to it, a gaze

01:31:13.320 --> 01:31:16.680
[Guest]: that has not so far received as much space as it should.

01:31:16.680 --> 01:31:20.120
[Guest]: So I'll name Parvati Sharma, who's now written a book on Jahangir or Ira Mukherjee, who's

01:31:20.120 --> 01:31:21.700
[Guest]: written about Mughal women.

01:31:21.700 --> 01:31:25.920
[Guest]: And it's fascinating because they bring a completely different perspective to this,

01:31:25.920 --> 01:31:28.280
[Guest]: the same material I would have approached in a certain way.

01:31:28.280 --> 01:31:30.920
[Guest]: But because they are women, they bring a completely different angle.

01:31:30.920 --> 01:31:33.120
[Guest]: And it's an angle that's been missing for too long.

01:31:33.120 --> 01:31:34.440
[Guest]: And it needs to be rectified.

01:31:34.440 --> 01:31:37.280
[Guest]: A man can do his best to try and see it from that perspective.

01:31:37.280 --> 01:31:42.520
[Guest]: But naturally, having more women historians has its own advantages as well.

01:31:42.520 --> 01:31:46.160
[Amit Varma]: And on that note, let's get back to your narrative and to our male protagonists.

01:31:46.160 --> 01:31:52.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about how after the Bahmanis fell, how Bijapur and you know, how the different

01:31:52.440 --> 01:31:56.640
[Amit Varma]: rebel sultans, how they evolved in different directions, for example, Bijapur almost seems

01:31:56.640 --> 01:32:02.760
[Amit Varma]: to sort of use faith as a weapon of real politic, Yusuf Adil Shah declared Bijapur a Shia state,

01:32:02.760 --> 01:32:06.680
[Amit Varma]: which was also very interesting, because at that point, there was still the pretense of

01:32:06.680 --> 01:32:08.440
[Amit Varma]: the Bahmani Empire going on.

01:32:08.440 --> 01:32:14.240
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, he had two masters nominally, which is a Bahmani king and the Shah of Iran.

01:32:14.240 --> 01:32:20.680
[Amit Varma]: And is this in any way analogous to a dilemma that Muslims face right up to the 20th century,

01:32:20.680 --> 01:32:23.780
[Amit Varma]: where you are part of whatever nation state you're part of?

01:32:23.780 --> 01:32:27.680
[Amit Varma]: But you know, like with the Khilafat movement, you saw a dilemma sort of playing out that

01:32:27.680 --> 01:32:31.680
[Guest]: you're also part of the larger Qaum, so to say, which is what, you know, right wing Hindutva

01:32:31.680 --> 01:32:33.400
[Guest]: people keep using against Muslims.

01:32:33.400 --> 01:32:37.800
[Guest]: What was the great Golwalkar Savarkar argument, which is that, oh, you know, to be truly Hindu

01:32:37.800 --> 01:32:41.800
[Guest]: or Indian, you need to have not only your birth here, your home here, but also your

01:32:41.800 --> 01:32:42.880
[Guest]: place of worship.

01:32:42.880 --> 01:32:45.880
[Guest]: This has to be a motherland and your fatherland, which is not the case for Muslims.

01:32:45.880 --> 01:32:50.440
[Guest]: If you're bowing to Mecca, which is in a foreign country, then your loyalties are suspect.

01:32:50.440 --> 01:32:54.880
[Guest]: And for Muslims, of course, you know, not acknowledging that global aspect of it is

01:32:54.880 --> 01:32:59.880
[Guest]: impossible because, and silly, in fact, it's silly and no, but it's impossible to the idea,

01:32:59.880 --> 01:33:02.000
[Guest]: which is that why must you be either or?

01:33:02.000 --> 01:33:05.640
[Guest]: The whole point of this country is there's so much diversity, so much language, so many

01:33:05.640 --> 01:33:07.840
[Guest]: castes, you can be all of it at once.

01:33:07.840 --> 01:33:10.960
[Guest]: You can be, you know, a North Indian, I'm a South Indian, but that doesn't make you

01:33:10.960 --> 01:33:12.160
[Guest]: or me less Indian.

01:33:12.160 --> 01:33:13.920
[Guest]: I can be at the same time a Malayali.

01:33:13.920 --> 01:33:18.280
[Guest]: And this is an example my ex-boss Shashi Tharoor often gives, which is, you can be a good Hindu

01:33:18.280 --> 01:33:19.480
[Guest]: and you can be a good Indian.

01:33:19.480 --> 01:33:21.840
[Guest]: You can be a good Malayali and you can be a good Indian.

01:33:21.840 --> 01:33:23.320
[Guest]: None of these are in contradiction to each other.

01:33:23.320 --> 01:33:26.800
[Guest]: It's okay to have multiple layers of identity.

01:33:26.800 --> 01:33:32.480
[Guest]: But of course, for the right wing, the fact that Muslims have a non-Indian link as well,

01:33:32.480 --> 01:33:36.860
[Guest]: which is an identity that rises above any one given nation state, that becomes a little

01:33:36.860 --> 01:33:38.080
[Guest]: bit of a problem.

01:33:38.080 --> 01:33:41.600
[Guest]: But as I said, that it depends on how you want to look at it, because I don't think

01:33:41.600 --> 01:33:45.840
[Guest]: Indian Muslims are any less Indian because they have a place of worship in Mecca, or

01:33:45.840 --> 01:33:50.320
[Guest]: because many of them are descended from people who came from Iran or whatever.

01:33:50.320 --> 01:33:53.560
[Guest]: As I said, many, if you come to the South, the oldest Muslim communities have nothing

01:33:53.560 --> 01:33:55.320
[Guest]: to do with these later immigrations.

01:33:55.320 --> 01:33:56.760
[Amit Varma]: They've been here for thousands of years.

01:33:56.760 --> 01:34:00.280
[Amit Varma]: And there's a great hypocrisy inherent in these claims, because these claims are made

01:34:00.280 --> 01:34:04.080
[Amit Varma]: by people who are wearing clothing, which have come from outside, from the Middle East.

01:34:04.080 --> 01:34:05.080
[Amit Varma]: They're eating food.

01:34:05.080 --> 01:34:08.720
[Amit Varma]: I had a great episode with Vikram Doctor recently about the Indianness of Indian food, about

01:34:08.720 --> 01:34:13.080
[Amit Varma]: how so much Indian food has sort of originated in various different places and are still

01:34:13.080 --> 01:34:16.880
[Amit Varma]: nevertheless inherently completely Indian.

01:34:16.880 --> 01:34:21.240
[Guest]: Look at Bombay or Mumbai, where we now are, you know, the Ganesh festival just happened.

01:34:21.240 --> 01:34:23.760
[Guest]: You would have seen there were so many marigold flowers that were being used.

01:34:23.760 --> 01:34:24.920
[Guest]: Where did the marigold come from?

01:34:24.920 --> 01:34:25.920
[Guest]: South America.

01:34:25.920 --> 01:34:26.920
[Amit Varma]: It's only a 400, 500 year old flower.

01:34:26.920 --> 01:34:28.640
[Amit Varma]: That's the same point Vikram made in the show.

01:34:28.640 --> 01:34:32.960
[Guest]: We now use the marigold for all our rituals, but the marigold is not even an Indian flower.

01:34:32.960 --> 01:34:34.560
[Guest]: The potato is not Indian.

01:34:34.560 --> 01:34:38.520
[Guest]: You know, a lot of these spices that we, the green chillies are not Indian.

01:34:38.520 --> 01:34:41.480
[Guest]: You know, South Indians make sambar now with potato and tomato and onion.

01:34:41.480 --> 01:34:43.520
[Guest]: These were never there in the old version of sambar.

01:34:43.520 --> 01:34:47.560
[Guest]: These are vegetables that came, my grandmother tells me, growing up in the 1930s and 40s,

01:34:47.560 --> 01:34:50.400
[Guest]: they never ate potatoes and onions because they never came there.

01:34:50.400 --> 01:34:53.480
[Guest]: Once in a while, you'll see it coming from somewhere else in the country, but most of

01:34:53.480 --> 01:34:54.480
[Guest]: the time it was never eaten.

01:34:54.480 --> 01:34:58.840
[Guest]: It was never, the tapioca, if you go to Kerala now, what we call kappa in mean curry, which

01:34:58.840 --> 01:35:03.720
[Guest]: is, you know, tapioca with fish, it's considered like a staple quintessential Malayali dish.

01:35:03.720 --> 01:35:05.120
[Guest]: Tapioca came to Kerala in the 1880s.

01:35:05.120 --> 01:35:07.120
[Amit Varma]: Have you heard my episode with Doc?

01:35:07.120 --> 01:35:11.040
[Amit Varma]: I don't think so because he said all of this.

01:35:11.040 --> 01:35:13.160
[Amit Varma]: So let's, I think the episode's gone on for a long time.

01:35:13.160 --> 01:35:18.360
[Amit Varma]: So let's, we can kind of rush through this portion of history and sort of, so sum up

01:35:18.360 --> 01:35:22.520
[Amit Varma]: for me how this dynamic is playing out, these different rebel sultans after the Bahmani

01:35:22.520 --> 01:35:24.680
[Amit Varma]: Empire in the North Deccan.

01:35:24.680 --> 01:35:25.680
[Amit Varma]: What's really going on?

01:35:25.680 --> 01:35:26.680
[Guest]: What are the dynamics?

01:35:26.680 --> 01:35:28.000
[Guest]: Well, as I said, these are military states.

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:32.800
[Guest]: They have no grand agenda, they have no grand, you know, nationalistic principle, nothing.

01:35:32.800 --> 01:35:36.240
[Guest]: It's just that one set of elites is in power, somewhere else, another set of elites is in

01:35:36.240 --> 01:35:37.240
[Guest]: power.

01:35:37.240 --> 01:35:38.640
[Guest]: Lower elites are trying to claim power.

01:35:38.640 --> 01:35:40.000
[Guest]: That's what ends up happening.

01:35:40.000 --> 01:35:43.160
[Guest]: So the most striking figure is towards the end of the book.

01:35:43.160 --> 01:35:45.760
[Guest]: So the book is the subtitle from Khilji to Shivaji.

01:35:45.760 --> 01:35:51.040
[Guest]: Shivaji is the one where I end the book because what Shivaji is doing is for 400 years, 500

01:35:51.040 --> 01:35:53.440
[Guest]: years, the Deccan's been under Islamic rule.

01:35:53.440 --> 01:35:56.120
[Guest]: Now this doesn't mean the Hindus have been displaced.

01:35:56.120 --> 01:36:00.900
[Guest]: The best example is this little kingdom called the Garhwal Raj, which was in former princely

01:36:00.900 --> 01:36:02.400
[Guest]: state of Hyderabad.

01:36:02.400 --> 01:36:06.280
[Guest]: Now initially they were feudatories or vassals of the Kakatiyas.

01:36:06.280 --> 01:36:08.200
[Guest]: Then the Kakatiyas are displaced and the Delhi Sultans come.

01:36:08.200 --> 01:36:09.840
[Guest]: They start serving the Delhi Sultans.

01:36:09.840 --> 01:36:10.840
[Guest]: Delhi Sultans are gone.

01:36:10.840 --> 01:36:11.840
[Guest]: Bahmanis come.

01:36:11.840 --> 01:36:12.840
[Guest]: They start serving the Bahmani Sultans.

01:36:12.840 --> 01:36:13.840
[Guest]: The Bahmanis are gone.

01:36:13.840 --> 01:36:17.320
[Guest]: Finally, the Adil Shahs and the Qutub Shahs at various points end up being their overlords.

01:36:17.320 --> 01:36:18.840
[Guest]: They sound a lot like the Indian bureaucracy.

01:36:18.840 --> 01:36:19.840
[Guest]: Yeah, yes.

01:36:19.840 --> 01:36:21.200
[Guest]: That's the point I'm making.

01:36:21.200 --> 01:36:23.840
[Guest]: Finally they come under the hands of the Nizam of Hyderabad, who was an agent of the Mughal

01:36:23.840 --> 01:36:27.320
[Guest]: Emperor and they survive all the way till 1948.

01:36:27.320 --> 01:36:32.040
[Guest]: So something that existed in the 1300s, that same family ruling of the same 1000 square

01:36:32.040 --> 01:36:36.000
[Guest]: miles of territory has continued to rule all the way till 1948.

01:36:36.000 --> 01:36:40.440
[Guest]: So the top layer may keep changing and shifting and falling and rising, but just beneath that,

01:36:40.440 --> 01:36:42.120
[Guest]: there aren't that many changes.

01:36:42.120 --> 01:36:45.640
[Guest]: These are all very elite level changes and discussions that are happening.

01:36:45.640 --> 01:36:49.000
[Guest]: At the next level, things are pretty much, you know, they're in the hands of the same

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:50.000
[Guest]: family Muslims.

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:52.960
[Guest]: Hindus have not been displaced en masse or anything.

01:36:52.960 --> 01:36:57.400
[Guest]: What is interesting with Shivaji is that this Islamicate court culture that evolved in the

01:36:57.400 --> 01:37:01.520
[Guest]: Deccan, a very peculiar blend of part North India, part Persian, part Vijayanagar, all

01:37:01.520 --> 01:37:03.200
[Guest]: of it existed.

01:37:03.200 --> 01:37:07.560
[Guest]: Shivaji now wants to go back to a Sanskritized version of kingship.

01:37:07.560 --> 01:37:12.760
[Guest]: So he consciously starts avoiding Persian words and creates the Raja Vewahar Kosha,

01:37:12.760 --> 01:37:17.000
[Guest]: which is a Sanskrit dictionary, starts writing letters towards the end of his reign in Sanskrit

01:37:17.000 --> 01:37:21.040
[Guest]: to other northern kings because he's trying to construct a new court culture, a new way

01:37:21.040 --> 01:37:25.440
[Guest]: of doing politics inspired by Sanskritic Hindu traditions.

01:37:25.440 --> 01:37:31.360
[Guest]: So he wants the Rajputs and him and all these Hindu origin people to sort of, you know,

01:37:31.360 --> 01:37:33.920
[Guest]: stick to the Sanskritized version of things rather than the Persianized version of things.

01:37:33.920 --> 01:37:36.960
[Amit Varma]: And would you say this is similar to what happened in the early 20th century, the late

01:37:36.960 --> 01:37:41.800
[Amit Varma]: 19th century, when a lot of these groups tried to take Hindustani and separate Urdu from

01:37:41.800 --> 01:37:44.400
[Amit Varma]: Hindi and build some kind of separate Shuddh Hindi?

01:37:44.400 --> 01:37:48.880
[Guest]: Yeah, that begins in the 19th century, really, where you have this ultra Sanskritized Hindi

01:37:48.880 --> 01:37:53.080
[Guest]: being born and this ultra Persianized Urdu being crafted as a separate thing.

01:37:53.080 --> 01:37:56.320
[Guest]: Whereas in reality, they're children of the same mother and that mother was much more

01:37:56.320 --> 01:37:59.520
[Guest]: mixed up than either will admit, but this quest for purity.

01:37:59.520 --> 01:38:04.440
[Guest]: So that is largely a result of the colonial intervention as well, that's a later phenomenon.

01:38:04.440 --> 01:38:08.720
[Guest]: What's interesting in Shivaji's time, however, is that simultaneously with him in Golconda,

01:38:08.720 --> 01:38:13.480
[Guest]: we have two Brahmin ministers of the Qutub Shah called Madana and Akana and they're brothers.

01:38:13.480 --> 01:38:17.220
[Guest]: And one of them refers, talks to a Dutch merchant and he says, oh, look, all these Persians

01:38:17.220 --> 01:38:20.640
[Guest]: coming here, they make their money and their fortunes and they go back because those are

01:38:20.640 --> 01:38:21.640
[Guest]: their fatherlands.

01:38:21.640 --> 01:38:22.960
[Guest]: We have only this as our land.

01:38:22.960 --> 01:38:27.500
[Guest]: So we are much better in terms of we should be running this place properly.

01:38:27.500 --> 01:38:31.400
[Guest]: It's interesting because this is almost a Golwalkar-esque, Savarkar-esque argument from

01:38:31.400 --> 01:38:34.800
[Guest]: the 20th century, but we're hearing it in the late 17th century.

01:38:34.800 --> 01:38:40.360
[Guest]: So what it indicates is that at the elite level, there was some beginning of an identity

01:38:40.360 --> 01:38:44.880
[Guest]: that was in common, saying that something was missing.

01:38:44.880 --> 01:38:45.880
[Guest]: There was a sense of loss.

01:38:45.880 --> 01:38:50.360
[Amit Varma]: And these intellectual strains, therefore, existed from before, it's not like Golwalkar

01:38:50.360 --> 01:38:52.400
[Guest]: and Savarkar sort of, it began with them.

01:38:52.400 --> 01:38:57.800
[Guest]: They took it to a completely different level, which is by making more mass.

01:38:57.800 --> 01:38:58.840
[Guest]: Why is this mass now?

01:38:58.840 --> 01:39:02.440
[Guest]: Because we've now bought into this idea that the Sanskritic version of Hinduism is the

01:39:02.440 --> 01:39:04.640
[Guest]: version of Hinduism, which is not true.

01:39:04.640 --> 01:39:06.320
[Guest]: What happened to lower caste versions of Hinduism?

01:39:06.320 --> 01:39:08.240
[Guest]: What happened to tribal versions of Hinduism?

01:39:08.240 --> 01:39:12.080
[Guest]: You know, there are surveys in South India from 1915, as late as 1915, talking about

01:39:12.080 --> 01:39:15.680
[Guest]: how 80% people in South India did not subscribe to Brahminical gods.

01:39:15.680 --> 01:39:19.900
[Guest]: They had their local tree gods and local goddess of smallpox and things like that.

01:39:19.900 --> 01:39:24.760
[Guest]: But as education came in, they started Brahminicizing or Sanskritizing and giving up their ancient

01:39:24.760 --> 01:39:27.880
[Guest]: gods and becoming worshippers of Shiva, Parvati, Vishnu.

01:39:27.880 --> 01:39:32.440
[Guest]: So this happens simultaneously with that, where you have this mass reinforcement of

01:39:32.440 --> 01:39:35.920
[Guest]: the idea that the faith of the Brahmins is the legitimate form of Hinduism.

01:39:35.920 --> 01:39:40.880
[Guest]: Whereas in the earlier phase, what you see is this sense of, I think, what happened is

01:39:40.880 --> 01:39:44.960
[Guest]: that earlier, if you were under Hindu kingdom or a Hindu king, your patronage was limited

01:39:44.960 --> 01:39:46.320
[Guest]: to these elite groups.

01:39:46.320 --> 01:39:47.320
[Guest]: With the Muslims, there was competition.

01:39:47.320 --> 01:39:49.600
[Guest]: There were these Persians, there were these Africans.

01:39:49.600 --> 01:39:52.200
[Guest]: So you weren't quite the top of the chain, as it were.

01:39:52.200 --> 01:39:55.280
[Guest]: So that seems to have created a little bit of elite resentment, which is what you see

01:39:55.280 --> 01:39:56.680
[Guest]: in the 17th century.

01:39:56.680 --> 01:40:00.760
[Guest]: And Shivaji was definitely, therefore, when he says he's building a Hindavi Swaraj, he

01:40:00.760 --> 01:40:02.680
[Guest]: does therefore play up the idea of that.

01:40:02.680 --> 01:40:05.480
[Guest]: But it wasn't something for all Hindus against all Muslims.

01:40:05.480 --> 01:40:06.480
[Guest]: He employed Muslims.

01:40:06.480 --> 01:40:11.200
[Guest]: He had Qazis in, you know, the famous episode where Afzal Khan is sent to murder Shivaji.

01:40:11.200 --> 01:40:14.560
[Guest]: Now, if you look at it, Afzal Khan versus Shivaji, Muslim versus Hindu.

01:40:14.560 --> 01:40:18.360
[Guest]: But look at the people coming with Afzal Khan, Ghorpade.

01:40:18.360 --> 01:40:20.440
[Guest]: So Maharashtrian surnames, they're Maratha surnames.

01:40:20.440 --> 01:40:23.160
[Guest]: On Shivaji's side, Siddhi Ibrahim, it's a Muslim.

01:40:23.160 --> 01:40:24.160
[Guest]: Shivaji had plenty of Muslims.

01:40:24.160 --> 01:40:27.280
[Guest]: He had plenty of Islamic influences in his court as well.

01:40:27.280 --> 01:40:30.960
[Guest]: But he looked at power from a Sanskritic position.

01:40:30.960 --> 01:40:33.000
[Guest]: And that seems to have begun something.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:36.680
[Guest]: And simultaneously, you have similar trends in Golconda, which means that at that particular

01:40:36.680 --> 01:40:40.680
[Guest]: juncture, when the Sultanate is starting to collapse, when the Mughals are coming in violently

01:40:40.680 --> 01:40:46.440
[Guest]: from the north, there is this germination of a new sense of elite identity.

01:40:46.440 --> 01:40:50.480
[Guest]: I will not say it's a Hindu identity because there was no one broad Hindu community.

01:40:50.480 --> 01:40:53.640
[Guest]: For a Brahmin, a Dalit was as alien as a Muslim.

01:40:53.640 --> 01:40:55.240
[Guest]: There was no commonality between them.

01:40:55.240 --> 01:40:56.560
[Guest]: One could argue it's still the same today.

01:40:56.560 --> 01:40:57.560
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:40:57.560 --> 01:41:02.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think they see each other as part of the same ecosystem or whatever.

01:41:02.000 --> 01:41:04.600
[Guest]: So in that sense, there was something that was being born then.

01:41:04.600 --> 01:41:08.600
[Guest]: So I wouldn't agree with many people who say that, oh, you know, communalism is entirely

01:41:08.600 --> 01:41:10.240
[Guest]: a colonial invention.

01:41:10.240 --> 01:41:16.560
[Guest]: No, at the elite level, there seems to have been some, you know, some sort of minor flavor

01:41:16.560 --> 01:41:20.160
[Guest]: that seems to have been coming in at this particular time, which later assumed bigger

01:41:20.160 --> 01:41:21.960
[Amit Varma]: proportions in the colonial period.

01:41:21.960 --> 01:41:26.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, reading your book and listening to you now, on one hand, it seems as if, if you look

01:41:26.920 --> 01:41:30.680
[Amit Varma]: below the top layer, if you look below the Sultans and the people in charge, what you

01:41:30.680 --> 01:41:35.800
[Amit Varma]: really have are these vast, really solid waves of history moving, you know, like the same

01:41:35.800 --> 01:41:39.840
[Amit Varma]: bureaucracy serving different empires for hundreds of years, and so on.

01:41:39.840 --> 01:41:41.400
[Amit Varma]: And they are as they are.

01:41:41.400 --> 01:41:48.000
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you also see these powerful individuals like maybe Alauddin Khilji or

01:41:48.000 --> 01:41:51.680
[Amit Varma]: like Shivaji later, who have a huge impact on history just as individuals.

01:41:51.680 --> 01:41:56.080
[Amit Varma]: So what do you think of Thomas Carlyle's great man of history kind of the great man theory?

01:41:56.080 --> 01:42:00.680
[Guest]: See, I think they become great men largely in hindsight, in the sense that we pick and

01:42:00.680 --> 01:42:04.920
[Guest]: choose who we want to highlight, who we want to project more at the cost of whom.

01:42:04.920 --> 01:42:09.320
[Guest]: So as I said, you know, Shivaji dominates the Deccan landscape.

01:42:09.320 --> 01:42:13.360
[Guest]: The Deccan is often reduced to Mughals versus Shivaji, if you're lucky, otherwise, it's

01:42:13.360 --> 01:42:15.680
[Guest]: only Shivaji, especially in Maharashtra, it's only Shivaji.

01:42:15.680 --> 01:42:16.680
[Guest]: He deserves his place in history.

01:42:16.680 --> 01:42:19.000
[Guest]: He's a very charismatic, interesting figure.

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:21.400
[Guest]: But as I said, better historians have done good books on him.

01:42:21.400 --> 01:42:23.160
[Guest]: What interested me was, why only him?

01:42:23.160 --> 01:42:24.760
[Guest]: There are so many people before him.

01:42:24.760 --> 01:42:28.140
[Guest]: Why not Ibrahim Adil Shah II with his Rudrakshan Saraswati love?

01:42:28.140 --> 01:42:32.960
[Guest]: Why not Malik Ambar, the African who saved the Deccan for at least two generations from

01:42:32.960 --> 01:42:33.960
[Guest]: Mughal conquest?

01:42:33.960 --> 01:42:38.080
[Guest]: You know, these are people who also made history, but because they have no political constituency

01:42:38.080 --> 01:42:39.960
[Guest]: now, they've been forgotten.

01:42:39.960 --> 01:42:44.240
[Guest]: So the great men of history are also a reflection of our own anxieties, our own insecurities,

01:42:44.240 --> 01:42:49.120
[Guest]: our own sense of what we want to draw from history, rather than what actually happened

01:42:49.120 --> 01:42:50.120
[Guest]: in history.

01:42:50.120 --> 01:42:53.160
[Guest]: Which is why more and more people, at least with my first book and my second book, the

01:42:53.160 --> 01:42:57.320
[Guest]: idea is to pull these people or pull these stories out of the footnotes and give them

01:42:57.320 --> 01:42:59.360
[Guest]: the broad audience that they deserve.

01:42:59.360 --> 01:43:02.760
[Guest]: Because they don't deserve to merely be a footnote in a larger story of somebody else.

01:43:02.760 --> 01:43:06.120
[Guest]: They were actually independent actors in their own right, in their own time, they were the

01:43:06.120 --> 01:43:09.080
[Guest]: main actors and people who made history.

01:43:09.080 --> 01:43:12.640
[Guest]: We shouldn't put them into the shadow of any one great man or great woman as such.

01:43:12.640 --> 01:43:17.520
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you mentioned Ibrahim Adil Shah II, Ibrahim Adil Shah I died in a very interesting

01:43:17.520 --> 01:43:19.760
[Amit Varma]: way, which you described, but basically he fell ill.

01:43:19.760 --> 01:43:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And every physician who tried to cure him when they couldn't take his pain away, he

01:43:23.120 --> 01:43:26.580
[Guest]: had them trampled by mad elephants, which then led to a mass exodus of all physicians

01:43:26.580 --> 01:43:27.580
[Amit Varma]: from his capital.

01:43:27.580 --> 01:43:31.840
[Amit Varma]: He had no one to treat him and he died, which is a classic mistaking causation for correlation,

01:43:31.840 --> 01:43:34.120
